\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid1328737 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 My present address is 108 Chorley New Road, Bolton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Marital status?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I am }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And the year when you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  in 1928.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And the year when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 1902.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The place where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I was born at 11 Clarendon Place, Ledds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can you remember how long you lived in that particular house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
From the date of my birth... we moved to Harrogate, now you will be able to place this better than I. I remember George V being proclaimed in Ledds and I remember his Coron
ation when we lived in Harrogate, so we moved from Leeds to Harrogate between the death of Edward VII and the Coronation of George V. About 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would you actually be in Leeds or Harrogate in 1911, do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I think we probably moved in the Spring on 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can you remember why it was that you made that move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. My father was a director of Hepworth's, who are wholesale clothiers in Claypit Lane in Leeds and at about that time he had a heart trouble and he was advised to quieten d
own and from that time on only to work sort of half time, and having got along in the world to put it this sort of way he found a house in Harrogate which suited him and my mother and the family, and then he commuted between Harrogate }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  Leeds. But I think the primary reason was my father's health.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you make any further moves before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, we moved from one house in Harrogate to another house in Harrogate during the first World War, I should say in 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was that because it was a better house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, we rented the house which we originally occupied in Harrogate and eventually the house to which we moved came on the market and my father bought it, so we moved into the house which we bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I had one brother and 3 sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can you give me the order they came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I had a sister, a brother, sister, sister, and I was the youngest.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was the approximate spacing between each of the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The first 3 came at sort of 2-year intervals, then there was a 10 year gap before my sister was born, and I was born 18 months after she.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how old would your father be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 He'd be mid forties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Where did he originate from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 From Armley, which is a suburb of Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 He was a director of Hepworth's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What had his occupational career been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 He spent practically the whole of his life at Hepworth's. He went as a clerk, eventually became the Company Secretary with
 a seat on the Board.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he ever do any casual or part time work of any kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, he was a director of other companies, non-executive director of other companies, such as Petty's of Leeds and Thrift Stores of Leeds.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, your mother; can you remember about how old she would be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, she'd be 7 years younger than my father - she'd be in her late 30's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she come from Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 She came from Garforth which at that time was a country district about 10 miles south of Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she have any job before she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she do any work outside the home after her marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, she was a keen church worker in the Methodist Church, which took up a lot of her time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 This, of course, would be voluntary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, voluntary work. She had no paid employment after marriage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, there are several questions which relate to the house and the household routine, 
of the house that you spent the bulk of your childhood at which would be the Leeds house, wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can you tell me how many rooms there were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I just have to think about this. Downstairs: drawing room, diningroom, kitchen, butle
r's pantry, and so forth. On the first floor there were 3 principal bedrooms and a secondary bedroom, and on the second floor there were 4 bedrooms, including 2 servants' bedrooms, plus bathroom, you know, and things of this sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, did anyone else besides your parents and your brother and sisters live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, apart from staff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Your mother obviously had staff to help in the house, and these included living-in servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What exactly did the domestic staff consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
A cook; what we used to call a 'general' who was parlourmaid plus everything else except cooking; and what we used to call a 'mother's help'. They call them nannies, now, don't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How many of these people lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 They all lived in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And there were 2 servants' bedrooms, so presumably 2 would share a bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, they had their own bedrooms, but my nanny when I was a child - we had a sort of bedroom which was a night nursery, and she slept in the same bedroom as I did when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Where did these people eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
The cook and the general servant ate in the kitchen but - let's keep on calling her 'nanny,' shall we? - Nanny ate and lived as one of the family, as far as.... at the table, anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there a servants' hall or anywhere where they could sit when they weren't working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Apart form the kitchen, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother supervise all the housework personally or pass the orders through the...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, Mother did... yes, she would supervise the lot. Did
 the shopping and decided the order of going in and so forth. Yes, I would say she did the supervision.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel at ease with the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, very much so. As children we used to have lots of fun in the kitchen, perhaps more fun in the kitchen than we had elsewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How did the servants and the members of the family address each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
The servants in those days always referred to my father as 'the Master' and my mother as 'Madam'. My mother referred to the servants by Christian names and to Nanny always as Miss Thompson.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that any of these people was interested in you as a person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Very much so with my nanny. She really had a great deal of affection for me and if the truth be told I had perhaps more af
fection for my nanny than I had for my mother because I saw and lived with and had a lot more to do with my nanny. We were very close together, she treated me almost as her own child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you know if your mother gave any moral guidance to her staff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, she insisted - and this is rather strange in the context of 1970, but she insisted that they went to Chapel on Sunday nights, because they couldn't do on Sunday mornings because they had to do the work. But she was very keen that they should go to
 Chapel on Sunday nights and she was... mind you, I was brought up in a Nonconformist teetotal atmosphere, and she was very keen on abstinence from alcohol in the servants and was always telling them the dangers of that sort of thing. And on one famous oc
c
asion we had a very good cook who, for 12 months at a time would be a very good cook, then for 12 months she'd break out on gin and we'd find her flat on the kitchen floor. Mother used to search her room and find hidden bottles of gin in her wardrobe, and
 she with great ceremony poured this down the sink, and we put up with this, and so forth. Poor Sarah, they called her, she finished up in an inebriate's home I'm afraid to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When the servants had any free time - presumably they had free time to do what they liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When could they go out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
You know, I don't think it was terribly regulated; 'as soon as your work's done you may go out' sort of attitude and 'if you can arrange with Sarah, if you want Wednesday off make 
it right with Sarah and you may go' and so forth and so on. But I think most evenings they could go out apart from... I think Monday evening, or perhaps Tuesday evening was ironing and Friday evening was cleaning the silver, and those sort of things were 
sacrosanct. But otherwise they worked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother mind what the servants did when they were off duty, when they were out? Or did she mind what time they came back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, I think she was always anxious, or perhaps over-anxious for their welfa
re. She would warn them about the evils of men, in general, and certain types in particular. Whether they took the least bit of notice of her I haven't a clue. And she always insisted that if they had a young man they had to bring him into the light of th
e kitchen and she, Mother, had to have a look at them. The other part of the question just escapes me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she mind what time they came back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, very much so. If they didn't expect to be in by 10 they had to tell her they would be late up, and 
there was no such thing as staying out after 11.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The washing, I gather, was done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who, exactly, did that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We had a large wash-kitchen in the cellar, the old fashioned wash-kitchen. The general servant did it assisted,
 in her younger days, by my mother and a little later as my elder sisters got to be young women, they assisted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who was it who made or mended the family's clothes? Would there be any making or would it all be...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. Mother used to make fro
cks for my sisters, dressmaking, and Nanny used to look after my clothes and my youngest sister, Barbara, make and mend and darn and so forth, to look after us. My elder sisters when I first remember them, they were in their teens, you know, and they'd lo
ok after themselves as far as making and mending was concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who did the cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We had a cook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And she did it all, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 She didn't have any help from the...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 From my sisters? I think as a duty in their training
 Mother insisted that they should learn to cook. I think the cook regarded them as a very great nuisance, but my two eldest sisters, one week they had to assist the house-maid in bed-making and cleaning and these sort of things and the other one had to as
sist in the kitchen and they reversed the process each week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who was responsible for repairs and improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Very much my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he do anything himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. He was a very keen amateur joiner, he was very clever as 
a woodworker purely in an amateur way and he delighted in this. This was his recreation and his hobby and he taught both his sons the use of tools, and I'm very grateful to him for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Your nanny, what did her duties consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Primarily, looki
ng after my sister Barbara, who was 18 months older than I, and me. There was a day nursery and a night nursery and she was very much in charge of us. She taught us to read and write and prepared us before we went to kindergarten school. She nursed us, sh
e
 looked after us. Mother, at that time was very socially committed on what used to be called in those days 'at home' days. Every blessed day of the week you were visiting somebody's at home or it was our 'at home'. And the church work, and so forth, Mothe
r was out an awful lot and Nanny, really, her job was to be in loco parentis. I mean she took the load that many mothers would have carried themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about her hours of duty and her off duty time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Again, we regarded her as quite a member o
f the family, in the same way as my parents regarded their own daughters. Her name was Miss Thompson, my elders sisters always called her Tommy. We, the younger ones, called her Nanny, but the elder ones called her Tommy, although she called them Miss Kat
hleen and Miss Ruby. But like my own sisters, she could go out when she wished as long as there was nothing that needed her to stay in. she had quite a fair amount of free time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how much time would you say that you actually spent with your parents? Did you have a regular set time or was it rather a haphazard...?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I used to see quite a lot of my mother, particularly in mornings and I always had to be washed and scrubbed when anyone was calling to be produced to her friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would this be one of the nanny's duties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, yes. I saw very little of my father, who used to come home from business at about 6 o'clock in those days and the attitude in the house was 'now, behave yourself and be quiet, your father will be very tired when he co
mes home and won't want you making noise'. And he was very good to us as far as this world's things were concerned but he had no time at all for children and we had, after he'd had his evening meal, to go in and say good night to him and kiss him, then go
 to bed. So I didn't have very much contact at that time of life with my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about outings, for instance, with your parents, did you have any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. At this time my father bought a little house in Bridlington and every Good Friday of ever
y year we, the younger ones, with with Mother or Nanny to Bridlington. At that time Mother managed one house and Nanny managed the other. Half the family was always in Bridlington and the other half in Leeds and my father used to come over at weekends fro
m
 Leeds to Bridlington. And as kids we stayed in Bridlington from Good Friday until mid-September and the older ones used to alternate between the two. But we lived in Bridlington 6 months of the year in this house. Now, during that time my father was very
 
keen on travel and very fond of my mother - they were very fond of each other - and they used to do quite a lot of Continental holidays on their own. But those holidays we never, as children, went with them. He was glad to park us in Bridlington and make 
sure we were well fed and well clothed and happy, so he could go off with Mother and enjoy himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you see your parents in the nursery, or in other parts of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we, like all kids we used to dash round a bit. Mother always tried 
her best to come into the nursery and interest herself, and I'm sure she was a jolly good mother to us. And at weekends we saw them. On Sundays we had to get fell in, in a crocodile and walk from our home to the Chapel, which was in the middle of Leeds, w
h
ich was 2 1/2 miles away, and although there were trams running it wasn't quite the thing to ride in a tram on Sunday, so we walked there and we walked back, as a family. I remember as a child hearing my mother talk to her friends and I knew our nanny was
 thought to be well paid at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
20 a year, plus her keep and so forth. And I remember my mother saying you couldn't get a good cook for less than }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
18 a year, or a good housemaid for less than }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 15 a year. If you were prepared to train them you could get them fo
r a good deal less. This is just an illustration of the sort of money, the sort of wages that were paid and received in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What did your mother prefer, did she prefer people to come fully trained or did she like to train them herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, she liked them trained.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I have to ask one or two questions about the buying of clothes. When and where would you normally buy clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, the boys, because my father was closely associated with a manufacturing tailor, when we wanted clothe
s we went down to the factory and got fitted up. My younger sister, my mother would take her out to buy her clothes, to the stores in Leeds. Economically she loathed ostentation, she was an economical woman. My elder sisters... I tell you, when I was a ch
ild they were in their 'teens ...they had a dress allowance and were expected to buy their own clothes. I don't know what the dress allowance was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about shoes, buying your shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, again, at that time of my life my mother bought the chi
ldren's shoes, my own shoes and my sister's shoes. Again, my elder sisters had to provide their own shoes from their dress allowance, and my elder brother was working and, of course, he looked after his clothes of all sorts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how often did you have new clothes as a child? Was it quite a frequent ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, I don't think it was frequent. I think we had sort of new outfits every summer and new outfits every winter. And, of course, we were growing at this time and we grew out of clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I wondered whether, for instance, you had a new rig-out when it was the sermons at Church or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, my parents seemed to frown on this sort of thing, rather to be amused by people who turned out for sermons in that way. My people thoug
ht we ought to be kept unostentatiously tidy all the year round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Your father, you say, was keen on doing woodwork and so on, did he actually do anything in the house of a more mundane character in the household routine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Nothing at all as far as 
housework was concerned. He would have no part of it at all. He was the old fashioned type who thought this was women's work and not for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the decorating of the house, would you always have somebody in to do that, or would he possibly do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I think for the entertaining rooms and the principal bedrooms we always had professional decorators, but for the attics and servants' bedrooms and things like that my mother was a better hand at that sort of thing than my father was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were these the sort of things that she would like to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes, quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Now, obviously as you had a nanny, possibly this next question doesn't really arise. Did your father do anything for you as children, like dressing, undressing, bathing, reading to you, telling you stories, or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, nothing. He hadn't much time for children. The only thing that I ever remember him trying to do was to teach me to tell the time from his hunter which he pulled out of his pocket and said 'no
w, when the big hand is there and the small hand it there it is 4 o'clock, what will it be when the big hand is here and the little hand is there?' And I would say 'I don't know' and he'd say 'go away, you blockhead, I can't be bothered with you'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he ever take you out without your mother, or look after you when she was out and the nanny would be out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I only remember having one day out with my father in my childhood, when he took me on one occasion to a brother of his, my uncle, in Southport for the day. That's the only time I ever remember my father taking me out by himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there some special reason why he did it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. No, I think he wanted to see his brother and as he ... as a great trial to his immortal soul he took me along with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have any takes to carry out regularly in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I'm sorry to say, no, and I'd have been a lot better if I'd had. I'm afraid I got looked after and cleaned and washed, and my shoes cleaned and so forth and so on far too 
much. No, as I told you, early on my father taught me to use my hands, and I did things because I wanted to do them but not because it was a task.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You've said that your sisters did various aspects of the housework, as part of their training for adult 
life, I suppose, really. What about your elder brother, do you remember if he did anything ever at all, or was he treated the same way as you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, well, my elder brother left school when he was 16, and I would be only 2 or 3 or 4, I don't know,
 and soon after that in pursuance of his own career he left home and he wasn't much at home up to the date of his death, which was 1915, in the Army in France during the first World War.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did the older members of the family help you as the youngest member with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, my eldest sister, Kathleen who, praise be to God is still alive at the age of 81, was very helpful to me. She spent a lot of time with me; she was very fond of me, and helped me to read and things of this sort. She'd rather he
lp Tommy (or Nanny) with my primary ... sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \deleted\revauthdel1\revdttmdel1722125237\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cf0\revised\revauth1\revdttm1722125237\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 ...}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
 beginnings, and also she sheltered me. If I tore a hole in my trousers I would run to Kathleen to get it mended for me before my mother found out, and so forth. My other elder sister, who died last year 
in her late seventies, was just the reverse and I would prefer to say no more about her than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you help your favourite sister with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, yes. If she were going shopping and she said 'come along with me', I would be delighted to
 carry her parcels for her, and so forth and so on. But I had no tasks to do, I'm afraid, for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Very much so. Except on special high days and holidays and special occasions, staying up late b
ecause there was a little party or somebody was in, but ... I really forget, but we were taken to bed regularly and punctually and fairly early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it your mother or the Nanny or anybody else who put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Nanny. I would say goodnight to my mother, and having got to bed Mother would probably come up and just have a final word.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, I don't know, but when we left Leeds and went to Harrogate Nanny left us and then I was on my own, I think 
about this time. But I'm sure I should be doing ... I'd be 9 by this time, I'm sure I should be doing it before then. I just can't remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have a bedroom to yourself? You had the night nursery, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. Tommy, my nanny, slept 
in another bed in that room until I went to school, which would be about 6, and then after that I always had a bedroom ... Oh, after that for a year or two I slept in the same room as my elder brother, in 2 beds, until he left home and then I had a room o
f my own after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 There would, in fact, be adequate bedrooms for the whole family, wouldn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there any sharing, at all amongst, say, the sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I think my two elder sisters shared, had 2 bed in one of the rooms, yes. But my youngest sister had a small bedroom of her own, always.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Obviously, you were well fitted for sanitary arrangements in your house, unlike a lot of people at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, yes, according to the standard of that time, which would not be 
regarded as good standards today. We had an indoor... of course, we got hot and cold water, which we got from a damn great Yorkshire range when coal was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 1 a ton; separate water closet. There was a servants' water closet in the basement which the cook and the maid had to use, they could not use ours, but they ... there was only one bathroom, so they had to use our bathroom.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did the bathing have to be rationed out according to the hot water supply or ..?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I think it ran to about 2 baths per ni
ght, so that we all had a bath night and in those days it was regarded as sufficient for this world if one had I bath a week, unless one had been doing something dirty and required more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the eating arrangements? You would have your meals in the nursery as a small child, did you, or would you eat with the family?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we had our breakfasts, not in the nursery, but at a different time. My father ... in those days they used to be \{BLANK\}
 longer than they do now. My father would probably 
leave the house soon after 8 o'clock, and we would have our breakfast in the diningroom, as we called it, after he'd gone. He came home to lunch and we had a family lunch. We all sat down together at lunchtime, which was the big meal of the day. It was a 
d
inner, it was our dinnertime, and this was the substantial Victorian sort of stodgy meal. And tea, we had it before father came home, sometimes in the nursery, sometimes in the kitchen, sometimes in the diningroom. And then we had something to go to bed w
ith, probably bread and milk which was served to ruin all our teeth in the whole family, but this was the sort of thing they used to do in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about your father's meals, did he have a more substantial meal in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, he had a cooked meal, always, when he came home in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And who else would share that with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Mother. My mother would. She would probably have been out having a cup of tea or afternoon tea or something of this sort, and then have an evening meal, something of this sort, seven o'clock-ish, but we never sat down at that evening meal, the family.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Normally it was the diningroom, was it, where you ate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the cooking equipment? You had a range, you've already mentione
d that. Did you have a gas cooker, do you know, or any other kind of ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, we had a gas ring. I don't remember at that time before we went to Harrogate, I don't think we had a gas oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And this range was in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother, or did the cook, bake the bread for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it the cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. And my elder sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have homemade jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Always, yes. That was made by Mother, chiefly, she was a great stocker-up of jams. And i
f I can go into parenthesis there, an amusing little thing: I well remember my mother saying that strawberries ... they'd got to be cheap to make jam ... when they got to three halfpence a lb. It was time to make jam. Twopence a lb. was rather too expensi
ve. She'd wait until they got to 3-halfpence a lb. and then she'd start to make strawberry jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about bottling fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no, we didn't seem to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Pickling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I don't think we did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there any wine made in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, my ... as I think I mentioned previously, my parents were strictly - almost bigotedly - teetotal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there any mixing of medicine, herbal brews or this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, we used to get dosed with patent medicine
, far too much, I think. Beecham's pills were an ever-present help in time of trouble. Aconite and Belladonna were the things when you had a cold; Veno's Cough Cure ... these were the sort of things, these nostrums and patent medicines, my mother had a st
upid regard for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it your mother who determined this sort of thing rather than your Nanny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, very much so. Oh, yes, she was very much in charge of the medicine cabinet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you think that your mother and your nanny agreed over things in general?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I never heard a cross word between them. My mother ... I'd a great regard for my nanny and when she left us my mother ... my parents, but it was my mother's leadership ... when my nanny eventually got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 
Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 , they set her up in a
 little cottage in Wetherby, and I never heard my nanny lose her temper with my mother, she was a very patient woman. But I think they had a great regard for each other, and my nanny was of that generation who were brought up sort of 'God bless the squire
 and his relations and keep us in our proper stations', and she was quite happy to be that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your family have any home grown vegetables or fruit? Did you have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, in Leeds we hadn't ... we were within the urban part of Leeds. We 
had a back garden with alleged grass in it which just survived with difficulty, but nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 So that fruit and vegetables would be bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about tinned or dried fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, we used to have dried peas, I r
emember, often, and tinned salmon, and tinned sardines, but I don't think Mother kept a large supply of these sort of things. She would regard them more as emergency supplies when her housekeeping had just gone wrong a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about tinned fruit, was that \{BLANK\} or not, in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, I'd forgotten that. Tinned fruit was a great nursery treat, tinned peaches and tinned pears and so forth, with custard. Yes, we had those quite regularly and we were very fond of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of meals did you normally have? What would constitute an ordinary meal and what would constitute a special treat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, going through the day, for breakfast either/ we always had/porridge in winter, or what we used to call Force, in summer. It's this Kellog
gs now, the same sort of stuff, and always either something cooked a bit of bacon or perhaps a kipper, something of this sort, and some bread and jam and lots of tea. Lunch ... dinnertime, midday dinner, a bit of hot joint on Sunday, cold on Monday, stew 
o
n Tuesday, sausages Wednesday, boiled cod (hateful stuff) once, and so forth, plus in winter we had lots and lots of soup and plus a stodgy pudding of some sort, you know the old stodge; and for tea, as I say, sometimes sardines, or something substantial 
o
f this sort, plus bread and jam. Special treats - you're thinking about birthdays and high days and holidays - well, then bought cakes were the great things. The cook used to make cakes and so forth, but sticky things from the pastry shop were a great tre
at and we used to stuff ourselves with this rubbish, and birthday cakes and Christmas cakes and all that sort of thing, but we were not ... we were plain eaters. I think we ate far too much, but plain, plain food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, you wouldn't have facilities for keeping livestock, would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Hens, or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, I went through the motions, like all boys, of keeping white mice to everybody's horror for a little while, until I was persuaded out of it; and I went through the motions o
f keeping rabbits for a little while, but as for hens or livestock in a proper sense, no, there were no facilities.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you know anybody who did any poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Poaching? No. No, no, we were very much city dwellers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You wouldn't often eat altogether, would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Except at lunch time, dinnertime. The midday meal, we always had that en famille.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, think of lunchtime, then. Do you ever remember seeing your mother have less so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, no, no, no, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your father have bigger portions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No. He was not terribly interested ... I mean he was not a big eater. There was always ample for everybody and nobody, as far as I can remember, had to watch this, until World War I when, of course, we all had to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And that, of course, was rationing, not financial?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Exactly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was the atmosphere of the mealtime, could you talk during the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We did chatter, but if we got too noisy we were told to be quiet. Very much the atti
tude of 'little children should be seen and not heard', although I wouldn't like to create the impression that we were repressed in any way. We weren't, but we accepted the fact that when we were dining with our elders, our parents, we had to try and be o
n our best behaviour, and not have too much noise. And if got noisy we might occasionally have been sent out with our plate to finish our meal in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked, or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We had no choice. I'm thinking about dinner. This was it and you liked it, and if you didn't like it you still had to eat it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was the attitude if you attempted to leave some food uneaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, there was always the threa
t 'you'll have to eat it cold for your tea'. I don't think the threat was ever carried out. It was regarded as rather disgraceful if you didn't eat what was given to you and the old, old story was told, you know, 'many a poor child would be grateful for w
hat you've left on your plate', and moral lessons of this sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If there was something on the table, say, the salt, could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We could ask for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And you could ask for second helpings, presumably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taught to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and to sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, we were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Could you ever bring toys or a book up to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you were all seated at the table at lunchtime, did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Always, yes, we did. And we were very keen about it, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it your mother who served the meal, or did the cook or the parlourmaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The housemaid brought the food in on a 
trolly and put it on the table, and Father carved and my mother looked after the vegetables, and so forth, and the sweet or pudding, and do forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What order did she serve you in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 My father always first, then I don't think there was any order after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you were very, very young, before you could sit up to the table properly, can you remember what happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I had a high chair and sat at the table near my mother in my high chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how old do you think you would be when you graduated to sitting at the table properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, that's difficult, isn't it? I just don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did the servants have the same food as the rest of the household, but they had to wait until it came from our table to go on to their table, 
unless, of course it was something that could be ... steak or chops, or something. But as far as the joint was concernedthey had to wait until it had come from our table to go on to theirs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I know you didn't see a great deal of your parents and you ha
ve already told me something about your relationships with them. Would you say that your mother was an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I think she was. Like most children, we kept a certain amount back from her because we didn't want to distress her. We
 didn't tell her our naughtiness. If she found out she was understanding, perhaps stern occasionally but we didn't go and tell her our troubles unless they were big ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that you could share your worries with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I think I ... with my mother, yes, but I think I probably shared my worries more with my nanny and my sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And what about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh no, I was - I hope I'm not creating a bad impression of my father 'cos he was a very good man and he looked after us
 all very well. He did what was right and honourable, and so forth, but to the date of his death in 1929 I never knew my father. He was the last man I'd go to in trouble. I had to go to him in trouble, particularly in my undergraduate days when I was play
i
ng the fool a bit, but I had to endure some terrible dressings-down and then, having done his duty by my morally he would write out the cheque and say 'don't do it again'. But no, I only went to my father with my problems if there was nobody else to take 
them to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Affectionately. I'm not quite sure what that question means. Daddie }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  Mummie ... we very much loved our mother, we very much respected our father, but there was a terrible gap, age
 gap between us. It may well be with the younger ones, I've indicated that my youngest sister and myself were the children of fairly old parents and I think after a ten years' gap between the three and Barbara and myself, I think we both, Barbara and I ca
me as a bit of a shock to them. I don't think we were planned, anyhow, putting it no higher than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother and sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, we were ... They tried to teach us to act courteo
usly towards one another, and my youngest sister and I, like all children, we fought with each other and teamed up together against the rest of the world. And my eldest brother we regarded as something wonderful. He was the Big Brother; he was always the 
wonderful fellow who always had to threepence to give to his little sister and brother. And as I've indicated, my eldest sister, I had the greatest regard for her and my other sister, unhappily it was not quite the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taught to hit back if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, we weren't. We were rather taught to turn the other cheek. I'm afraid that lesson didn't sink in with me, but if I came home with a bloody nose and I explained the Tommy Jones attacked me in the school yard and I had to de
fend myself, I was told it would have been much better if I'd told Tommy Jones to be a good boy and walked away, but I never accepted that sort of teaching, but that was the sort of thing that was given to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was this from your nanny as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 O
h, no. Nanny, just used to cry over me and wipe my blood off my face and mend my torn clothes and be sorry for me, particularly if I lost. (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, my father was ve
ry, very keen that I should read medicine and I wasn't. I felt that I had no vocation for medicine, but he was an overwhelming type of person and because I really daren't say 'no' I went up to university and read medicine and it was 3 years before I rebel
l
ed and he rebelled as well, because it took me 2 years to pass my first M.B. which should have taken 12 months, and it took me another year to fail my second M.B., by which time my father realized that it wasn't for me. But he very much wanted me to be a 
physician.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, in the arrow, non-conformist tradition. Lying was the unforgivable sin, so I'm afraid I've been unforgiven a few times. Turning the other cheek was regard
ed as a good thing. They would have been pleased if I'd shown any interest in the Methodist ministry which, of course, I didn't. It was before the medicine lark came along. And respect for elders. I'm talking about the usual Victorian traditions, which wa
s common; but I think they tried to unculcate the Golden Rule, anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was their view of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, this was ... two things. It was against all religious teaching and also it was jolly bad manners, and it was a thing that only louts did. 
The only reason for swearing was that you hadn't learnt sufficient adjectives, you couldn't find the right adjective so you were so lazy you swore, and this was regarded as rather contemptible.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When grownups were talking were you allowed to join in their conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Only when you were invited, but they often invited us into the conversation. But one listened until one was asked the direct question.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When very yo
ung, get sent to bed early. Occasionally, physical punishment and because my father had a heart condition my mother had to administer the physical punishment, which consisted of a cane on the bottom, and it hurt. And I'm quite sure now that she spoke the 
truth when she said it hurt her more than it hurt me. But my mother was the administrator of corporal punishment, but not often. Otherwise, being sent to bed early or, in the nursery, being stood in the corner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of punishments would merit getting the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Lying; stealing - when I say stealing, pinching things out of the larder and so forth without asking; bullying of my younger sister; things of this sort. This merited corporal punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Your father didn't administer corporal punishment; did he administer punishment in any other sort of way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, he left it very much to my mother. When he was displeased with me he just went quiet and let me know that I'd been cast out from the company of the elect for the time being. His favourite expression was I'm not angry, I'm hurt'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It's father funny, I was punished lots of times, but the only one that sticks out ... that that question provokes is the time that I wa
s punished for something I didn't do. Isn't it funny how you remember these things? I remember we were in Bridlington in this cottage and my father was with us for the weekend and he set the alarum clock to catch an early train from Bridlington back to Le
e
ds on the Monday morning, and the alarum clock failed to go off because it had been altered and by a process of elimination nobody had done it, therefore, I had. It must have been because it was nobody else. I remember being thrashed for that and I haven'
t
 really forgiven my parents for that after 65 years (laughter). But I don't recall anything else. Oh, I remember once being defiant to my mother - I don't know how old I'd be, I could be 8 or 9 - and my mother had ordered me to do something and I'd refuse
d
 and she said 'you'll do as I tell you', and I said to her - I'm ashamed of it now) - I said, 'we'll fight it out' to my mother. My mother got up and got this cane and she said 'right, we'll fight it out', and she thrashed me 'till I was blue, and I deser
ved every stroke of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You didn't resent being thrashed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, no, no. I don't think I bore any resentment at all. I got away with so much that I ought to have been punished for that I think as a child I was philosophical about ... as the burglar says 'It's a fair cop'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Would you say you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents equally, or did one play a more important part than the other? I think that my good manners, if I have any, that was the only part of my un
bringing that I remember from my father. He couldn't bear ill manners at table or anywhere else, and he taught me to behave myself at table and with my fellows, in my family and with other people. He taught me to dress correctly. I remember when I was in 
m
y 'teens he found me with a ready-made bow tie, which he threw in the fire. And he said 'if ever I see you wearing a ready-made tie or a dickie front again I'll cut you dead in the street. That was my father. But as for learning to live in this world of o
urs, being kind and understanding, this was very much Mother's part, rather than the more formal way of how to use your knife and fork.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you had a birthday would it be different from any ordinary day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. We always had a party. We alway
s had our friends in for a birthday party. And at that time the day nursery had been ... we moved the day nursery into a bigger room, and it was a lovely time. We used to have ... I don't know ... 12 or 20 kiddies, friends, in for birthday parties. Birthd
ay parties were quite the thing and if you had plenty of friends you seemed to be going to a birthday party quite frequently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have presents from people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. Little presents from our childhood friends. This was the thing to do, take a pre
sent or bring a present. And from our brothers and sisters, always. From our parents, usually utility presents. We were given what was thought good for us rather than what we would have liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can you remember anything you did with your mother and father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, no. Christmas Day was a glorified Sunday. We went to Church in the morning and had a wacking great Christmas dinner, always with a turkey and so forth and so on, and stuffed ourselves with food, sang carols round 
the piano in the afternoon and had a party tea, and went to bed gorged, I'm quite sure with too much food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It was strictly a family day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You didn't have people coming in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You had a piano. Did you have any other musical instruments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
My mother played the guitar, indifferently, but enjoyed it. Apart from that, no. And my 3 sisters and my brother, we all went through the horror of learning to play the piano. None of them were gifted, none of them had a vocation for 
it. They all got to The Bluebells of Scotland stage and stuck there, or a simple hymn, and had to be taken by the ear, I believe, to do their practise, so much so that my the time the youngest one came along, myself, my mother said ' you shall learn to pl
ay the piano if you ask to learn to play the piano and if not, not', so I was spared that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, not any more than families sing: hymns round the piano on Sunday evenings, carols, as I say; a simple ballad. 
Mother had a pleasant little voice and when she was entertaining my father would accompany her in a pleasant little Pale Hands I knew and all this sort of nonsense, but with no great ability.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 But you did make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, yes, of that sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents ever play any games with you? Either indoor or outdoor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't know how old we were when they taught us to play Whist, and we played cards with them. We played funny games, children's games, Happy Families,
 and I forget the names of the other children's card games. And then we were taught to play Whist. Outdoor, no. My father had no instincts for games or sport, he rather thought it was a waste of time, so that he didn't participate with us outside. And he 
thought - I think he was right, perhaps - what time he had to give to me he taught me, as I say, in a workshop which he had, to use my hands and I regarded it as great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was yours a household in which there were books about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, the usual non
sense. I don't mean that literally. The Dickens, the Thakerays, the Walter Scotts and so forth and so on. Modern novels had to be approved of in the reviews in the decent newspapers before they were allowed in but if they were given a good review, allowed
 
in the house, and they were not put away at weekends or anything of this sort. And our book - shelves were always full of many interesting books. Quite a lot of them are still on my bookshelf today and they don't remain there unread, some of them, even no
w.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You had newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Which newspapers can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
With the non-conformist liberal tradition or mainstay ... Father's mainstay was The Leeds Mercury, which was the radical newspaper in Leeds, and The Yorkshire Post, which w
as regarded as a necessity in the West Riding of Yorkshire, but its editorial opinions were frowned upon because it was Tory newspaper. But Sunday newspapers were not allowed in the house. This was regarded as the wrong thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Rubbishy magazines we seemed to have, Home Chat, Pearson's Weekly, Titbits, boys' magazines; Boys' Own Paper, Chums, The Scout, and so fort. Mother had the family magazines, you know, the predecessors of the present glossies. My father took the Spectat
or, and one or two other weeklies of that nature which I just forget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother and father both read to any extent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, they were great readers, both of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did they ever read aloud to you as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, Mother used to do. 
I had quite some periods of illness in my time and I can remember her reading to me for hours on end, bless her, on those occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember there being a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I remember my maternal grandfather dying, at a great age, a
nd I remember my father and mother going to the funeral which they didn't talk too much about. Funerals were a distressing thing, in their view, to children. I remember when they came home asking in a bright voice if they'd enjoyed themselves, and being t
o
ld that that was quite the wrong question to ask. I remember neighbours dying, and all the blinds being pulled down in our own house in respect for the neighbour. But those were the only sort of funerals... the only things that just occur to me as far as 
death was concerned, as it affected a child.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember anything about what the practices were as far as wearing mourning goes? Anything at all of the traditions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, I remember when my maternal grandfather died both my mother and father 
went into mourning for some months, but I can't remember for how long. My mother into black; my father quickly edging off onto a black armband. But this was some ... it was more than a week or two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, the only time we were ever put in mourning was in 1916 when my brother was killed in France.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And of course, you were considerably older then, weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taken out visiting people? Wereyou taken out to visit friends or neighbours or relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, we had to go ... Aunts, I had 3 or 4 aunts in Leeds and we used to go and see them; some, because it was a duty, others because we liked them. This maternal grandmother and grandfather were very much a duty. They were frightening, very old. Of 
course, when you're 5 or 6 anybody over 60 is very old, but they were rather formidable old people, very kind. My grandfather always sort of found a shilling in his pocket when we went to see him. And he had a large garden which we used to be turned loose
 into. I remember he grew beautiful strawberries and had fruit bushes, and so forth, which he let us loose in. But it was a bit of a trial to go and see my grandparents, the only grandparents I had because my paternal grandparents had died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Why do you think that it was a trial?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I think we had to be scrubbed and on our best behaviour and to show Grandma and Grandpa what nice kids we were. And if we had forgotten ourselves, as we regularly did, we got chided for letting Father and Mother down in fro
nt of Grandpa and Grandma and this was a bit of a .... I think this,; perhaps, was the background of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother and father always take you, or did you sometimes go on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We always had to go on our own on our birthday, to be given birthday wishes and the shilling, but otherwise our parents took us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about visiting friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, we were in and out of our friends' houses all the time. I had an uncle who lived next door and we were in and out of each other's houses all
 the time. And it was a very close Chapel community. A lot of people who were not related we called Uncle Sam and Uncle Dick, who weren't our uncles, and so forth, but we were on that sort of relationship with them. This was informal visiting. Formal, if 
you can call it formal visiting where children are concerned, really consisted of children's parties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about your parents' friends, were you taken out to visit them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't recall so. No, it would be very rarely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taken out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, I think my sisters were, and my youngest sister was, but I hated shopping then, as I do now, and I always ducked then, as I duck with my own wife now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember any outings or holidays, apart from your summer home at Bridlingt
on? Do you remember any other sorts of activities that you would do, say, on a Bank holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, there used to be an August Bank Holiday Gala in Roundhead park, which is a big park in Leeds. This was a 'must'. We used to always go to the Roundhead P
ark Gala. And then, my parents were not against the theatre, but it was a rarely. We always were taken to a Christmas pantomime at one or other of the Leeds theatres and also, before cinema came along - and this dates me, doesn't it? - we had a thing call
e
d Hamilton's Panorama which came to Leeds once a year. It would take me far too much tape to tell you what Hamilton's Panorama was, but that was another 'must'. But those were outings to the theatre. Occasionally, flower shows, which were a bore. But the 
exciting things were the Roundhead Gala, the panotmime and Hamilton's Panorama.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you ever go away for a holiday other than to Bridlington?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 At that time no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How did you used to spend Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we used to play in the back stree
ts, play in the back garden with our friends and so forth, kicking a ball about, catapults, and so forth. Saturday afternoons we used to .... I think we stayed in on Saturday afternoons, I don't know why. I thinking about when we were 5, 6 or 7. And the g
r
eat excitement on a Saturday afternoon was the arrival of a big hamper. My uncle, who incidentally was the grandfather of Susan Hampshire, the actess, George Hampshire was a wholesale greengrocer in the market in Leeds and each week he used to send up - w
hich my mother bought - a hamper of fruit and vegetables, and so forth, and we used to wait for this hamper to see how we could raid it before anybody got at it. This is my memory of Saturday afternoon; Uncle George's hamper, has it come yet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Chapel in the morning, Sunday School in the afternoon. We didn't go to Chapel in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have special Sunday clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. I was dressed, Heaven help me, in sailor suits, dark blue in winter, white on summer day
s in summer when you haven't to sit down anywhere for fear you'd dirty your backside, until I got ... I don't know, 8 or 9, and then I was put into, of all things, an Eton suit for Sundays. And these were very much your Sunday clothes. And parties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about playing games at any time on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, in the house. We could play the childish games of cards, but we hadn't to be noisy. This whole idea of 'have a good time but don't let the neighbours next door know you're having a good time' attitude. I'm being cynical, there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, your parents thought it was wrong to ride on a tram on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did they think it was wrong to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, except for servants, of course. It was part of the condition to which they had been bo
rn for them to work, but other work had to be very necessary and then it was excusable, but unnecessary work upstairs was regarded as not the thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was their attitude towards their own pleasure on a Sunday, was pleasure permitted as part of the Sunday, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't think their mental attitude included the thought of pleasure on a Sunday, it was more duty. I've recited Chapel morning and night for them and they took their turn in bringing the parson home for lunch, which was another great
 trial for we kids. But when we were in Bridlington on the parada, they would walk out on a Sunday afternoon and listen to the band, but anything exciting, or going off on trips, or anything of this sort was not a very good thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was your father confirmed in his regilious observances as your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
More so, as far as outward show was concerned. I would say that my mother was a more religious person than my father, but my father was more punctilious about the observance of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did the Sunday School have any outings during the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
One Sunday School trip per annum, which consisted in going in horse-drawn charabancs out to ... now, where did we used to go? Temple Newsam, which is a park just outside Leeds. On one famous occasion the
y took us, I think, by train to Scarborough, but this was quite a fantastic thing which we looked forward to, probably, for weeks. And you made sure you didn't miss a Sunday School for the requisite nine weeks before the trip, or else you were disqualifie
d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What other social activities were there organized by the Chapel, that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, in this period, until we left Leeds in 1911, not much. No, I can't remember another. I seem to remember Chapel anniversaries where one sat down befor
e, or after, or during, or something, to a wonderful boiled ham and tea, where the ladies presided at long tables with - what do they call these great things that they put tea in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 An urn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Urn. Tea urns, and it was very important to get invited t
o preside over a tea urn, and the kids used to have ... it was great fun. That was a social activity of the Church, but otherwise I don't remember much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, very m
uch so. I was taken by the scruff of my neck very early in life and told to 'sign here', where I pledged total abstinence for the rest of my life, and I satisfied my conscience when I grew up that that was got under duress and I'm afraid I'm not a teetota
ller and I'm not ashamed of the fact that I was made to sign something that I did not quite understand at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What activities did the temperance club have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, they had a sort of ... boiled ham seemed to come very much into the \{BLANK\} p
icture, doesn't it? (laughter) Tea parties of this sort, and little lectures on the evils of drink. I'm not trying to impress that I think they were a lot of horrible people, they were very nice people who did these sort of things, but terribly narrow, bu
t believed quite firmly in what they were trying to do for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you belong to any other club organised by the Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, not by the Chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was Grace said at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Always, at all meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who was it that ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 My father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We turn from that to politics. I gather your father was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you know why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The main reason I think with all of 
us in our political views is the background in which we were brought up. He was brought up in a radical tradition. He regarded the Conservative Party as the party of the privileged, the lazy, the people who'd been born with silver spoons in their mouths, 
a
nd he regarded the Liberal party as the party who were out to improve the lot of those who wished to improve it. He hadn't much time for social security, as we'd call it at the moment, of helping lame dogs who weren't trying to better themselves, but he b
elieved the liberal legislation was for the good of the mass of the people, particularly those who were attempting to improve their position in life, and so forth. I think this was his background.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about your mother, did she show any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No. She was a Liberal because my father was, and didn't quite know why, remembering, of course, that women didn't have any vote at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 She would have a vote in 1918, that was the first time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she use her vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, by which time ... she voted by secret ballot but I've every reason to believe that she didn't vote for the Liberal Party.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Have you any idea ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I think she was Conservative by that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about your father, do you think he ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, I think he stayed a Liberal all his life. I think he got less and less enchanted with liberalism particularly in the Lloyd George days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And he would vote Liberal presumably, would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you know if your father felt 
himself to be under any kind of pressure to vote for the Liberal Party, on account of his connection with Hepworth's, for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I don't think so at all. I don't think he had any pressure whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was he actually a member of the Liberal Party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he ever work for the party at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, occasionally I remember him going out canvassing, I think, more on municipal elections than general elections. I remember him canvassing for town councils.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was he connected with the town council at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, he never offered himself for election.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother ever take part in any activities of this kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your father or mother take part in any political activity other than at an election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't think they did. They were not politically minded, really. They didn't get hot under the collar about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When they weren't working how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 They went to the theatre, perhaps once a week. They were home
 birds, really, in the evening. They were very fond of each other's company; they read together; they read aloud to each other; and they were very fond of chess and whist, in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You say your mother did a lot of work connected with the Church,
 and with these at homes, did she have any other specific interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't think she did, you know. No, her family was very much her life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself, other than going with your father to the theatre and such like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, only except women's sewing parties at the Chapel, and these at home things and so forth, but I could never think of Mother going anywhere by herself outside purely women activities.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your father get home from work at a regular time each evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, it was round about 6 o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how many evenings a week did he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, every evening, either at home or going to the theatre with Mother. He wasn't a club man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he ever take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No. I think he always had health problems, but he regarded, I'm sorry to say, games and sport as necessary to keep one's muscles working, but otherwise a great waste of time and he always thought there were better ways of keeping one's muscles
 exercised than playing games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he ever attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no, no. He was very anti-gambling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents belong to any savings clubs? You know, sickness or funeral benefits, anything of this kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. No, not at all. My fa
ther was a very prudent man as far as money was concerned and at that time he had covered himself, particularly, with life insurance because he thought that his health would be such that he might go a long time before my mother, which indeed he did. But n
o, he was a saving type and a careful man, but he was very much of a self-help. He didn't require anybody to tell him how to save on how to invest his money, in his view.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Coming back to you again, who did you play with when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 My s
choolfellows at kindergarten school; my cousins, the Hampshires, who lived next door; and I had several friends who lived in the same street or adjacent streets, and those that have not died are still my friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Where did you play, normally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As
 I indicated before, kicking a ball about in a back street and breaking neighbours' windows, and so forth, that was part of it. In our back garden or somebody else's back garden, or more organised games quite near to us, within 10 minutes was Woodhouse Mo
or, which was a big open park space where we used to go and play unorganised football and unorganised cricket, you know, and this sort of thing. Childish sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about when the weather was bad, did you play either inside in your home or in the other children's homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. We'd always plenty to ... of toys, construction toys like Meccano and building blocks and so forth and so on. We seemed to lead a full life. It's no use my telling you a story and my memory fails me just how we did b
ut we seemed never to be at a loose end of what to do. I can't go much further up that street than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The outdoor games that you played would be the usual things like football and so on, would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have any sort of particular tricks that you used to get up to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Tricks in gamesmanship, do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I was thinking more the sort of mischievous things which seem to ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, we were little devils. At one time we took an interest in chemistry. Chemist
ry consisted of making explosives, as far as I remember. Potassium chlorate, if my memory serves me right, was a very good one which we used to make little piles of and drop bricks on which created loud explosions and all the tradesmen's horses in the vic
i
nity immediately bolted. That was great fun. We also - you know, they talk about juvenile delinquents today! - the catapult craze came along and our targets were usually the insulators on telegraph poles. If you broke an insulator on a telegraph pole that
 
was a good score. We were too young ... the boy scouts had just been formed - I think the boy scouts were formed in 1908 and years later I became a boy scout, but at this time we were too young, so we formed our own boy scouts, quite unofficial. We aped t
h
e big boys of 12 or 13 by being little ... we used to pinc broom handles and march up and down. In the early days scouting was quite a marvelous thing. In Yorkshire ... I found it didn't happen in Lancashire ... the day before bonfire night was call the M
i
schief Night, and Mischief Night we always took a delight in sewing up one's sisters' and brother's pyjamas, making apple pie beds, plastering treacle on neighbours' front door handles, ringing the bell and running away, tying up gates, and things of this
 sort, which was always accepted as part of the fun on Mischief Night. And of course, often neighbours lay in wait for one and one got boxed ears, but that was part of the hazzards of the fun. I don't think we really did anything more dreadful than that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You remember, we were talking about the question of behaviour, and so on, at the meal table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I should have asked you about when could you leave the meal table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We had to wait 'till the end of the meal, we were not allowed to leave 
unless something of urgency, such as getting back to school, or something, if the meal had been delayed, then we asked permission to leave the table. But normally we had to sit quietly until everybody had finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And did you then have to ask, or wait for a signal from your father to get up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If Father got up we all got up and if we wanted to go first, of course, we had to ask permission to leave the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, when we were in our ordinar
y clothes, and so forth we weren't told to keep clean and we used to get dirty and get our knees scratched and so forth and so on. But when we were in our Sunday clothes and our second best and so forth, we had to take care to look after our clothes, and 
so forth, and got scolded when we didn't, as we often didn't. We got scolded for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you free to play with anybody you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Broadly, yes, but sometimes we were criticized for playing with rough boys or errand boys, or boys that would teac
h us bad language, and so forth. I don't think we took much notice but we were told that there were people that it wasn't quite the thing to ... there was a certain unspoken snobbery about that, I agree.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would that apply as far as the errand boys wer
e concerned, or did they have some particular habits which were objectionable, for your parents to ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't think they pinpointed any objection, except that I think errand boys and so forth probably - and in fact did - have more money than we had
, would buy Woodbines and probably have things of this sort, habits that our parents didn't want us to acquire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You've told me about the organizations at Church that you belonged to and about how you had your mock boy scouts organization. Did you belo
ng to any youth organization while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Let us just clear this thing. I think in terms now of almost pre-school and kindergarten days, you see. Because we came to Harrogate in 1911, so I'm talking about until I was about 9 years 
of age. That's the period I'm thinking of now. There was an organisation in Leeds which was called The Spartans. This was a boy's organization with a religious background which had a Sunday School on Sunday afternoons and run by a rather worthy man and wo
m
an, a spinster and a schoolmaster who used also to invite us to their homes for coffee and buns and improving games, and so forth and so on. And the Spartans were supposed to also cultivate the habits of the spartans. The reproval was if you burst into te
ars, or were hurt, or cried because you were a cry-baby 'Spartans don't do that'. That sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I see, it was an organization for young children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Boys, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 For specially young boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And it wasn't affiliated to any other organization, it was quite independent, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
It was independent of any church, yes, but it was very much of a religious background. We sort of sang hymns on Sundays and had improving talks and so on and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 This mock boy scouts, that was also while you were at Leeds, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And you joined the boy scouts ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As soon as I was able, when we came to Harrogate, about 1911, 1912 I joined the Boy Scouts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you belong to any other organisations about that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About that time, no. Later I became a member of the Junior Y.M.C.A., but this was probably when I was 14 or 15.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You've told me about keeping white mice and rabbits. Did you have any other hobbies as a small child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We went through t
he phase of stamp collecting. Egg collecting, raiding birds' nests and collecting eggs and so forth; cigarette cards; picture postcards was a great thing for children in those days, collecting them in albums, picture postcards. Nothing else occurs to me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The cigarette cards, was that because ... did your father smoke?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You got these from people outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Outside, yes, we used to beg them; 'please, have you got a cigarette card, Sir?' sort of business. And then, of course, there 
was the swopping, which was a great thing, to collect a set. To collect the things in sets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you go fishing, or bicycling, or walking at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We didn't go fishing, except.... When you say fishing I presume you had in mind river fishing. No. B
ut when we were at Bridlington, as we were every year for 6 months we did a lot of sea fishing, going out in the cobble boats fishing most days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As a family, do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, my brother and I. My elder brother, when he was with us, or my fathe
r would take me, or my elder sister would take me. Mother didn't ... hated it, and so forth, but fishing was quite a thing, in the sea. River angling, no, I was never ... never taught that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you have your own boat at Bridlington, or did you hire it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, we used to hire them. The fishing cobbles, they used to take about 20 people out, you know, a sailing cobble, and it was 6d. for a few hours out in a morning or an afternoon. That's what we used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
At school. Again, kindergarten-wise, only playing kindergarten games. This was the kindergarten school in Leeds. When we went to Harrogate I went to a boys' school, which I'll pursue in due course as to what we did there, but when we went there, of cours
e, school games: cricket, football, the usual school games I participated in, not with any great success but I was interested. But my keenest thing when I was a young boy and, indeed, until I went to University, was swimming. I was a very able swimmer and
 eventually I represented the University and represented my county at swimming. But that was my great interest as a young boy, was swimming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You've told me about going to the pantomime; did you go to concerts or musichall at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Music halls, no.
 music halls were regarded as - and I believe it's true at that time - something rather rough and unpleasant sort of places. Concerts, no not a lot. I can't recall going to concerts of serious music, serious singing. I'm sure I went to a few but I had, an
d still have I'm sorry to say, I'm musically illiterate. Even to this day and it's a great sorrow to me, it doesn't mean much to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the theatre?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As a child very rarely to the theatre. Again, we were in Bridlington for the summer we us
ed to go to the Pierrot shoes, of course, which were common in those days, and entertainers who were the successors of the Pierrots; and occasionally we would be taken, as a great treat, to a musical comedy or a farce, Charlie's Aunt, or something of this
 sort. But theatre visits, until I was 14 or 15, were rarities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And you mentioned this Hamilton's Panorama, what was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It was a most amazing thing. On the stage there were two rolls, vertical rolls, one either side, and they rolled across th
e stage from one roll on to the other wacking great scenes. Really, it was scene shifting from one roll to the other and there was a lecturer. And they'd roll on the scene of Mount Vesuvius in eruption and the lecturer would tell us all about Mount Vesuvi
u
s in eruption. And then they'd roll onto Niagara Falls and the lecturer, with his pointer, would tell us all about Niagara Falls; and more grissly subjects, The Horrible Murder by Dr. Cripin, and these sort of things. But they'd roll these blessed things 
across the stage and the pictures on canvass were as big at the stage, and the lecturer did his stuff as they came across. They were the predecessors of the cinema, or the bioscope as it used to be called when it first came along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of a building would this take place in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 In a large theatre. I remember it, particularly, in the large, old-fashioned, very old-fashioned theatre in Leeds call the Coliseum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was this something that went on all the year round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, no, they visited for perhaps 2 or 3 weeks in the year. We used to look forward to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Because you went to Harrogate when you did, can you tell me whether your leisure-time interests as a child, you know, the sort of playing routines and hobbies routines and this sort of thing, did they alter quite considerably with the move.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, it seems to me in retrospect quite a water-shed, that move. It seems to be a feeling that I ceased to be a little boy, a very little boy at that period and a started feeling a big boy. There
's that sort of feeling. And when we went to Harrogate - again in retrospect I think my parents were rather ill-advised - but I was sent to a private school. In those days Harrogate was chock-ablock with private schools. These were schools for children up
 
to the age of ... ordinarily children left school at 16 ... but they were private enterprise schools unsupported by any public authority and some are good, some are very bad. The one I went to had a very able headmaster who had a very ill paid and very ro
t
ten staff. But my view was that they were supported usually by the petty bourgeois and small tradesmen types whose children perhaps could not get entry into the secondary schools of that time, or where the snob value of not being in a secondary school, be
i
ng in a private school and wearing a school cap was rather amusing. We went through the weigh-in in turn of taking the Oxford local Preliminary Junior and Senior, as it used to be called then - the Oxford Senior was comparable to the G.C.E. of later years
.
 But it was the exception rather than the rule for boys to take the G.C.E. and this was terribly handicapping for those of us who did because we thought we were good. We thought that those of us who took the G.C.E., or the Oxford Senior as it was called a
t that time, we thought we were good, and only when we got into competition later at University and so forth, that we found out how very poor we were academically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As we are on to schools, shall we deal with that section?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Certainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I gather that first of all your tutoring, you got a little bit from your nanny, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Before you went to school at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I could read and write, in a way, before I went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you were having lessons from your nanny, about how much time in the day would you devote to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, an hour in the morning and an hour in the afternoon, something of this sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And this, of course, was at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did any other children share the lessons with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, only my sister. My sister Barbara was 18 months older than I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of things were you taught? Was it just reading and writing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, reading and writing. I well remember we had a reading book, a primer reading book which had been handed do
wn through all the family and the joke was that we had got to - what was it we used to say? - Oh, 'have you got to damp grass yet?', because somewhere, halfway through this primer there was a story about the cat sitting on the damp grass and when you got 
t
o damp grass you were halfway through this primer, you see. And all of us, in turn, we got as far as damp grass. And we were given, also, given little Bible stories and so forth, but I don't think we were asked to do any writing, any composition or anythi
ng of this sort by Nanny. But we went to a kindergarten school when we were about 7, I think, in turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
In the course of your tuition from your nanny, did she emphasise certain things as being important? You know, manner, or anything of this kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, more so than any wish to press on with the academic side. 'Manners maketh man', be a little gentleman and always remember that little gentlemen don't do this, and so forth and so on was constantly being plugged into us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How did you feel about your nanny, as a teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, I loved her very much and she never got cross with me and was very patient with me, and I thought 'well, poor lass, she's got to do this, I'll put up with it, I'll go along with her because it's part of her business', bu
t I was never a scholarly child at that age. But I never resented it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of background had your nanny got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 She was a country woman from the village of Helmsley, which is a village in the North Riding or Yorkshire and I believe her father 
was a farm labourer or something of this sort. And she had, I think, been a village girl who'd been intelligent at the village school and had left her village, a) to earn money and b) to acquire a little bit of ... shall we say polish, or something that s
he wouldn't, probably, have got at home. I think this was her background. And eventually she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
 a blacksmith in Wetherby when she left us. She had no academic qualifications at all, but she was well spoken, nicely spoken, with a North Country accent like myself, but she ladylike in a nice sort of little way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she come into the household when your older sister started to need a nanny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, she came into the family when I was born, and my youngest sister was 18 months old. My mother hadn't ha
d a nanny before that. I think at just about that time my parents were getting to a position where they could afford that sort of help. Probably they wouldn't have been able to contemplate it earlier in their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Have you any idea how they came by her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I haven't the least idea. I don't know. I just don't know that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It's intriguing, isn't it, that a village girl should have come into the family like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I guess, it's purely a guess, but I should think they advertised pr
obably in some Methodist journal or something of this sort, but that is purely guess - work, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You went to school when you were about 7, was this this one private school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, this was in Leeds still. This was a kindergarten school wh
ich was within a quarter of a mile of where we lived and it was quite an amazing school for that time. It was run by 2 very able women, Miss Gardiner and a Miss George who had studied Montessori methods and were, I believe, looking back now, well ahead of
 their time as far as day schools were concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Sounds rather like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well ahead of their time. And it was a mixed school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About how big?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 They had, I think ... I think 50 or 60 children went there and they had one or two assistants,
 but the two principals were this Miss George and Miss Gardiner. And I think it was quite splendid for its generation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of hours were you at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Nine 'till 12 and 2 'till half past 4, something of this sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I see, a full school day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How did you get to it? You walked, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, it was within a few minutes of where we lived, actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did anybody take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, not ... You see, I was taken by Barbara who was 18 months older than myself
. When she started, well, someone took her at first, but as I say, it was within a few minutes' walk of home on quiet roads. There was not much traffic about in those days. No, I think we went by ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You came home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
You say in retrospect you think it was a school well ahead of its time. Thinking about how you felt about it when you were actually there did you like it? How did it strike you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, it was fun. It was fun, there was a lot of pla
y ... I'm not an educationalist as you are, but we used to do a lot of playing, educational playing, and so forth. But the groundwork was pretty good, I think. My colleague and people I remember at kindergarten school - most of them stayed, of course, in 
Leeds - but they were always readily accepted at Leeds Grammar School. The preparation was good enough for them to be readily accepted when they were 11 or 12 at Leeds Grammar School, or Leeds High School if they were girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that the assistant teachers were as good as the principals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no. They came, and they went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were particular things emphasized there at the kindergarten, manners or tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 This was always borne in on us, personal cleanliness particularly, and avoid
ance of bad language and slang. Slang was regarded as a very bad thing, and we had to, in the presence of the principals, avoid using popular expressions. Not bad words, but slangy words were regarded as not quite the thing that was good for one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the actual way that you spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
There was no question of acquiring an accent or a long 'a', we were North Country people and this was far more important that one's grammatical construction was correct, rather than that one's accent was correct.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If you did anything there that the teachers disapproved of, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
We got put in the corner. Those dear old ladies who ran that school - they weren't old at all, I suppose, but all grownups were old - had a wonderful habit of shamin
g one into tears for one's bad behaviour, making one thoroughly ashamed of oneself for letting the side down; for letting your father and your mother down, or letting the school down. I think it was mental bullying more than anything else, you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there any form of punishment at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, not at that school, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were the girls treated in the same way as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. I think at that age I don't look back upon it to realize the sex differentiation at that age. I can't recall any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of offences would merit ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, cheating; copying; petty theft, stealing one's neighbour's pencil or India rubber or things of this sort; personal grubbiness, failing to wash one's hands and keeping oneself as tidy, as children po
ssibly can do. Those were the sort of things ... the sort of traps I usually fell into.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents show an interest in the work you were doing at that school, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't remember them being terribly interested, and I don't seem to rem
ember that they had such things as 'Parents' Days' or anything of this sort. I don't seem to remember that. They had ... all our neighbours' kids went to this school, they all had a great regard for it and they all felt 'well, they're all right as long as
 
they're there. That's it, we've paid the fees and let them do the job and I'm sure they'll do it well'. I don't think there was much interest. The old, old story of coming home for lunch 'and what have you done at school this morning, dear?' and nobody li
stened when you told them. You know, that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was your nanny still there at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did she show an interest in what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. She was very anxious that we should scintillate. Not that we ever did, but she was anxious that we should do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would it be true to say that the other children came from similar types of home to yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Very similar, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did the teachers single out any of the children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, I don't think so. I can't remember them pushing on the brilliant ones, or giving special attention to the duller ones. No, I can't remember that happening. We seemed to all get the same treatment. No, I can't remember any differentiation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there any ganging up, or grouping up of children in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, we had our little gangs and ... yes, we used to refer to ourselves as gangs, but it hadn't an evil connotation. Usually neighbours' boys: Our gang was a better gang than the ot
her gang, but I don't think we ... we'd fight in the playground like all kiddies will occasionally, but we weren't our to do other gangs down, but we'd be boastful that, ah, we could get better cigarette cards than they could, or better birds' eggs than t
hey could, and we were probably braver and bigger and better, and so forth, but ... Yes, there was that sort of grouping, but it wasn't an evil sort of ganging.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you stay at this school, then, until you went to Harrogate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Until I went to Harrogate, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And then you went to another private school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about that school? This was a private school, a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, a boys' school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And it took you right up to university entrance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was that far away from where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. When we first went to Harro, in the first house we lived in it would be 20 minutes ... mile, mile and a half away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And did you walk there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Always walked, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Alone, or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, yes, unles
s we just casually met somebody who was going to the same school, then we'd go across together. Harrogate, you know, is a town surrounded by a big common called The Stray and we used to walk across The Stray to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you go home for your midday meal there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of hours were they, was it similar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, 9 'till 12 and 2 'till half past 4, something of this sort. And then, of course, we used to bring home preparation work, home work we used to call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What did you think about this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
At that time we were proud of our school and we thought we were good. And I told you the headmaster, a man called Charles Rogers, was a very able teacher. He was a graduate and he had been a form master at Leeds Modern School, 
which was a secondary school, and came to Harrogate and set up this school on his own. And I'd say in those days there were dozens of them, dozens of these private schools. And how he lived I just don't know. I do know this, that the fees when I first wen
t
 to school were 3 guineas a term, including books. Including the use of text books and stationery. And when I left to go to university at 17 the fees had only gone to 5 guineas a year. How the man lived I just don't know, but he did. He ran a little motor
 
car. His wife, I believe, was said to have a little money and that was probably the reason, otherwise thinking back I don't know how he managed to run the place. He had a very, very indifferent set of assistant masters, usually a bit down at heel, a bit g
r
ubby; clearly throw-outs of failures who couldn't get employment in public authority schools, I would think. And some of them used to leave very suddenly and very mysteriously and there were whispers about drunkenness or homosexuality or all sorts of thin
gs. They were a poor lot, were the assistant masters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 How big a school was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
There'd be about 100 boys there. In an old house, ill-adapted; adapted, but by this day's standards you would probably want to be sick by the look of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that there was a great lack of facilities in the school when you were attending it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, strangely enough we didn't, but when I look back I am horrified. The clockroom, summer and winter, had never anything but a cold tap, and washing oneself i
n the middle of winter under a cold tap! Well, it makes me sudder now, even to think about it, but we didn't think we were deprived, or anything of this sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, of course, the same would be true of the public authority schools as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Proba
bly so. Probably so. The lavatories were across the school yard, and rain, hale or snow, one had to make a dash for it across a very large school yard to get to the lavatories. But this was regarded as normal, we didn't think it was .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If the teach
ers were a rather peculiar lot themselves, did they try to emphasise particular values in you? You know the same sort of things ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We always had a disregard for the assistant masters. There were those whose preparation you had to do, because the ca
ne was used quite frequently in those days. If you didn't do the preparation for some assistant master you got caned, for others you didn't. So you did the preparation for those that would care you and you found very good excuses for not doing the homewor
k
 for those that were soft. Regularly the headmaster would find that a class was falling behind his required standards, and he would take over that class for a term and pull us up by the roots of our hair, bring us up again. And it was fantastic how when M
r. Rogers took a form for a term how we all started getting some work done and showing some results. And then he would go to another form to pull that out of trouble and we would slip back into the slough again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did he emphasise matters of behaviour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, he was particularly interested in our behaviour in the town wearing a school cap. If any boys were reported to him of acting the fool, or acting like louts in the town and so forth, he was the old type who believed in corporal punishment and dish
ed it out. I always remember, his cane he called Little Willie and his motto was 'Where there's a Willie there's a way'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there a good deal of punishment? You said the care was used quite freely. Were there other sorts of punishment as well, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, the punishment, as I remember it, were detentions for bad behaviour or laziness, or any of the schoolboy sins we got detentions, which was half an hour at the end of afternoon school. But 3 detentions a week by ... on the 3rd detention by a f
ormmaster, onehad to go to the head to report that this was the 3rd detention this week and his classical question then was, 'Well, now, boy was it for cheek or for impudence?' It was a Morton's fork, whichever you said was wrong and you got four on the b
ackside and told to behave yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of offence would merit getting the cane, apart from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Again, the schoolboy offences of pilferage, bad language, insolence, insubordination, those sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about bad work itself, was there any punishment for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Only to ... for untidy work, do it again. Bad work - otherwise failure to absorb what you'd been taught and clearly demonstrated, no, I don't think so. I don't think so. And there was a tremendous variation in forms
 between the top and the bottom, and the sluggards were allowed to stay so, I'm afraid. The head was only keen on ... His attitude was, 'there you are, boy, there's the food, if you won't eat it I can't make you'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents begin to show more interest in your schoolwork as you grew older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. I'm thinking personally, now, in my 'teens. I indicated to you my father had a great wish for me to read medicine and he was very keen that I matriculated as early as possible and in those days it wa
s not unusual for boys to go up to university at 18 plus. And he used to interview the headmaster quite a lot. He got on personal terms with him, he used to visit our houses. And he was always pressing to get some more work done, to make sure you'd get th
e
 required number of credits in the Oxford Senior, as it was called then, to give you matriculation exemption. And in fact I didn't 'till I was 17 and this was a great disappointment to him, but this was, I think, because he wanted to get me launched into 
my profession and off his back as early as possible.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were there any sort of open days or anything of that kind at that school? Any opportunities for parents to meet teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Not formally, no, not formally, in the open-day method. No, there weren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of homes did the children come from who were at that school? Similar to yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, It's a horrible expression but for want of a better expression, upper middle class, plus the children of small tradesmen, shopkeepers and so forth and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were there any gangs there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, we had a school troup of scouts, which we were very keen about, some of us more than others. Yes, we ... I think our gangs there were the people who went home in the same direction. This sort of crow
d went home this way and that sort of crowd went home that way, and we were stacked together and we thought we were good and they thought they were good. But there was no gangsterism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You were 17 when you left that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 That was when you went on to university?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I went to Leeds, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If you could have stayed on longer at that particular school would you have done so? Would it have been of any benefit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. I think the last year, from 16 to 17 I was a nuisance to the sch
ool. I was put in a private room to cram for the examination. No, I think the head would have much preferred all his boys to leave when they were 16 and the ideal of the head was to get school leavers jobs as bank clerks or something of this sort, non man
u
al employment. And in those days bank clerks were, I think, more highly regarded than they are now. If he could get a boy a job, a leaver, in a bank, this was jolly good, without an Oxford Senior, Local or anything of this sort, but just the fact that he'
d got that sort of employment, I think the headmaster thought 'well, I think this is as much as I can hope for of this lot of indifferent people' (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You went on to which university?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you stay at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I stayed at home. I traveled, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And you were there for 3 years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Three years, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did that, then, complete your formal education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, I did some - I'll just go on a little if you'll explore this, but I did a bit of reading at home to get a quali
fication in anything, which was entirely different later, but my formal education was completed then. I went to a medical school in Leeds, but I had no vocation for medicine. I hated it and I failed my first M.B., the first year, got it the second year. T
h
en I started on my second M.B. and I was making equally show progress there, playing the fool, I'm afraid to a great extent 'cos I had no interest. And as I told you, I was then a well known competitive swimmer and I became captain of the University swimm
i
ng club, chairman of the athletics committee; in fact I was very busy at University doing everything except what I would be examined in with the usual results. Now, at this time my father was getting very angry with me, I was getting very angry with him, 
b
ut at this time he .... Just about this time my father and my mother both became interested in Christian Science. I don't want to discuss that, it always worried me for years afterwards. But because they were interested in Christian Science they lost all 
i
nterest in their son becoming a doctor. So that eventually my father said 'Do you want to go on with this? I'll see you through if you want to but you'll have to work a jolly sight better than you are doing', and at that stage I said 'no, I've no interest
'
, and I want to pack it in'. And he said 'right, you shall pack it in, I've done what I can for you now you must decide for yourself what you want to do and don't blame me if you make a mess of it another time'. Shall I pursue my career from there, or not
?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 There are just one or two questions I should like to ask arising from that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 If you'd had a free choice of discipline at the University do you think you would have been happier pursuing a different academic sphere?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, quasi-academic. I w
as always, as I indicated earlier, I was always useful with my hands and if I had any ability at all it was in the direction of mathematics. I always wished to be an engineer, and if my father had said 'you go up to University what do you want to do?' I w
ould have asked to go into the Department of Engineering.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And you think you would have ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Enjoyed it, and I would never have been in the first class honours list, but I would always have been in the pass list, I'm sure about that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you attend any part time education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 After I'd left the University?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. When I left the University I determined to find a niche, if I could, in engineering. I would then be about 20, and I found somebody in Leeds, Bramley, whic
h is a suburb of Leeds, a working-class suburb of Leeds who had a small engineering establishment, what we call a jobbing engineer. That is to say, any job that comes along. And at that time - I think it's gone now, in fact I'm sure it has - but there wer
e such things known as Gentlemen Apprentices, whereby paying a premium you could start and apprenticeship later than the normal 15 years of age. And so, with my father's ... it wasn't much money, sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 
\'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 50 premium or something of this sort, I became a gen
tleman apprentice with this firm of Hurst Brothers in Bramley, and I served my time and 5 years later I became a partner with this man with whom I'd served, and the firm became Hurst and Walker, and some 4 or 5 years later I bought him out. He emigrated, 
actually, to South Africa, a very able practical engineer without any academic background. I bought Hurst out and carried on this engineering establishment up to the early 30's. I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  in 1928 and I was running this business until the early 30's when
 the time of the depression came along, and business didn't fail but it stopped making money. I was losing money and my accountants saw the light for me and said 'look, you'd better get out whilst you can get out'. So I sold out and got out. I sold out fo
r
 very little, but I got out in about 1933, by which time I had a wife and daughter and it was very ... my father died in the meantime ... it was a very worrying time for us. Now, for this next 2 years I just took any job I could to keep the butcher paid a
n
d the rent paid, you know what I mean. In fact, I sold motor cars; I acted as a technical representative for a large engineering firm in Leeds. These were jobs not that I wanted, not that I particularly liked, but jobs that were necessary to pay the butch
e
r. Then, in the mid-1930's, I think 1936 when the re-armament business started, the Air Ministry were advertising for temporary staff with engineering ability and background and I got a job as a production engineer with the Air Ministry, and went to Londo
n
. And this I rather did do well in. I left my wife and daughter, they went to live with my widowed mother then, and I was in lodging houses in London. And with plenty of leave, they used to come and see me and I used to get home once a month, something of
 
this sort. And I stayed with the Air Ministry, which later became Ministry of Aircraft Production, until the end of the War, until 1945, by which time I'd become an assistant director of engine production and I saw myself ending my days in the public serv
i
ce. During the War we had all sorts of people sent to us from industry to show us how to run the Civil Service. You, I know, have suffered from our type of people telling you how to do your job (laughter). And one of these men was a man called D.P. Wellma
n
 who was a managing director of a Lancashire engineering work in Blackburn, and he came ... a really high powered man ... who knew damn all about the way we had to do things, and for my sins I had to be very close to him, and my job was to say 'I'm sorry,
 
Mr. Wellman, we can't do it that way'; 'I'm sorry, Mr. Wellman, but before we can do this we must consult ...' and so froth and so on, you see. And he used to say 'well, no wonder we're losing the War. People like you ... Hitler's laughing', and so on and
 
so forth, but eventually he realized I was useful. And in 1944 a question was asked in the House of Commons by some opposition man who was trying to make trouble, as to just what Mr. D.P. Wellman knew about aircraft engines. And the Ministry defended him 
a
s, of course, they always defend Civil Servants. But after a question like that is asked a man must leave, so Mr. Wellman left. And a year later, just as the War was finishing I got a cryptic letter, typical letter, from Wellman to say something like this
:
 'Dear Walker, if you are sick of the job you are doing and would like to earn an honest living for a change, write to a man called D'Arcy Madden at Hick Hargreaves in Bolton. I think you might be interested.' So I just cast an arrow into the air to this 
unknown man D'Arcy Madden in this unknown town of Bolton to tell him that Mr. Wellman had told me about an unknown job that might interest me. And eventually D'Arcy Madden sent for me, and he was president, then president, of the Bolton }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  District Engineeri
ng Employers' Association. And I came up to see him, and I was very off-hand and I said, 'what is this job?' I'm not terribly interested but as a matter of courtesy to Mr. Wellman I said I would come to see you'. And he told me what the job was, to repres
e
nt the employers in this area in their negotiations on wages and conditions, in their negotiations with the trade unions, and rather to my surprise the job was offered to me, and I refused it. D'Arcy Madden pressed me, and I said, 'Look, I'm not giving up
 
acquired pension rights, which I can't take with me, and the salary you are offering is not sufficiently attractive to compensate for that'. And eventually ... we to'd and fro'd and nagged and nattered to each other in quite a pleasant way, and they bough
t
 me 10 years added pensions rights to start me off and gave me a salary which was ... I couldn't refuse. And this is how I arrived in Bolton in 1945. And for the first time in my life I found my vocation. I found that I had ... natural modesty doesn't for
bid me saying that I had a vocation for industrial negotiation and conciliation. That's the most circuitous way that I found myself where I did and found that this was a thing that I could do well, and this is what I did until last year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you doing several things the last few years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Whilst I was in Bolton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. You were connected with the Chamber of ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Commerce. My main job, I came as a secretary of the Engineering Employers' Association and then later I became the director. The
re wasn't a director when I came, it was really a change of title and status more than a change of job, except that I got an assistant who was called the secretary. But as part of the white man's burden in 1945 I was told 'sorry, old boy, but if we give y
ou this job, from the same office is run the Bolton Chamber of Commerce and you'll have to do that'. And the Bolton Chamber of Commerce, a very valuable organization, but without much money, and they sort of paid me, there's no secret about it, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 300 a year,
 which was enough to pay my wine merchant and my tabacconist, about. But it was the sort of thing one had to take when one accepted this main job with the Engineering Employers'. And in point of fact I found it very interested and I found I had, I think, 
a
 vocation for that sort of work, which was dealing with overseas trade, finding markets abroad, and so forth and so on. And in course of time, in the mid '50s, I was fortunate enough to become the president of the Association of Secretaries of British Cha
m
bers of Commerce. And this opened a lot of doors, social doors, and so forth. There's no money in the Chamber of Commerce, but it did a lot of things for me. I mean, my wife and I have been privileged to go to the Royal Garden Party 3 or 4 times, and we w
ent to the Lord Mayor's banquets, and so forth. Those sort of things were useful to us. The money aspect, of course, was piffling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Can we go back, then, to your first job, when you went to the jobbing engineer. When you first went there, what exactly did you have to do?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I'd got to put on a boiler suit and learn the ABC's of fitting, turning, tackling any job of manufacture under instruction; doing us I was told from a foreman; making myself ... trying to make myself forget the fact that I was 20 y
ears of age and that I had been at a redbrick university, and not trying to crow over younger boys who knew more than I did. And I went through the mill the hard way, like any other engineering apprentice would do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 8 in the morning, 'till 6 at night, 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid932031  1/2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9379319\charrsid932031  days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Saturday being the half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Saturday being the half day. And in those days, if the job wasn't finished as 6 o'clock, you just stayed 'till it was finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 A fortnight a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Paid, or unpaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Paid, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 It was paid, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, yes. I just couldn't remember for the moment. I think it was, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What sort of wage were you paid when you first went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 3 a week, and this was a lot more
 than I earned, but I think this was due to two things; first the small premium, which wasn't a big premium, only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
50; but also the fact that my employer, I think, realized that if I went through with this thing, he had in mind I'm sure that he wanted to g
et out and I would be a suitable candidate for buying his business from him, which in fact, I first went into partnership with him and eventually I did buy him out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 So you feel you were paid more than the work you did itself was actually worth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. For a year or two, anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What was the arrangement with your mother? Your father was dead by this time, wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you pay any of your earnings to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, no. Mother was living by herself at this time and w
as very comfortable off. And in fact the movement of money was, perhaps, in the other direction. Mother used to subsidise us, to a certain extent, in a nice way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you find it easy to get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 The younger apprentices, and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. I've always found it fairly easy to get on with people, both my social betters and - another nasty term - social inferiors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I gather you felt that your employer treated you pretty well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, in that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As far as money was concerned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, he was a blighter (laughter) He was one of the worst-tempered men I've ever met; terribly difficult, moody. It was very good for me to have served my time w
ith that man because I learnt to hold my tongue and put my pride in my pocket and swallow hard many times when I could have kicked him around. And I think, if I hadn't had a wife and baby at home I would have done, but I realized that perhaps I'd made a m
ess of things to start and I wasn't going to make another mess of this one, and I stuck it. But he was a terror, but a very, very good engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did other people find him difficult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did it produce a rapid turnover of staff, or were jobs too hard to come by for people to be able to afford to...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
You've put your finger precisely on it. In this day and generation nobody would work for him at all. But in those days anybody who had a job, they thought themselves very lucky to
 have a regular job, a regular wage and they just stuck it, because you couldn't walk nextdoor and get another job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As for the work itself, did you enjoy that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Very much, yes. Very much indeed. I loved the practical work, and I went to night cl
asses, and so forth, to become an associate member of the Institute of Mechanical Engineers, which I eventually did. But the practical work I loved very much. When I became his partner I had then to look after ... rather came out of the workshops, spent s
ome time in the workshops but spent more time in the office to take over the business side of the thing, which didn't appeal to me half so much, but I did it faithfully.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would you at that stage have to do things like costing and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, at that stage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Or did you have somebody to whom you could delegate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, no, we only employed about six ... four men and 2 young apprentices and myself. And no woman, we had to bash our accounts out ourselves on the typewriter with the two-fingers-and-damn-it method, you know, and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you actually belong to a trade union at any stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Or to an employers' body when you went into partnership?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. When I went into partnership, the firm - not individuals but firms - we 
were members of the Engineering Trades Association, which was the appropriate employers' organization. Although it wasn't a union shop. I don't think any of our chaps, any of our employees, were trade unionists. I don't think they were. If they had wanted
 to be there wouldn't have been any opposition. At that time trade unions hadn't got round to organizing small businesses such as ours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that the workers and the employers had the same outlook about the business and so on, or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, the employees were not interested in profits because they did not participate at all in profits. Their only interest in profits was that if we didn't make a profit they would be out of work. They were a good lot of chaps and we didn't have to slac
k. We had to discharge people in our time for playing the fool, or sitting down in the lavatory and not getting on with the job, those sort of things. Occasionally for pilferage; but broadly they were good, hard-working men. A good bunch of lads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest amongst them, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, I don't think so. They worked as a team pretty well. And in this spot where the workshop was, in Bramley, which is a working-plass suburb of Leeds, they belonged with their empl
oyers, to the same clubs. They went to watch the same football matches and sat side by side, and so forth. Class distinctions were very blurred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you feel that there was any distinction between a trained craftsman and a labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, very muc
h so. The trained craftsman, then as now, is a terrible conservative with a small 'c'. He has a great contempt for the unskilled or labouring type and takes great care, and I don't blame him, for making sure that the unskilled man does not prostitute the 
craft. That is the expression. Otherwise, does not do ... is not allowed to do the jobs that he, the craftsman, had to do five weary years as apprenticeship in order to qualify himself to do it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And were there undertones of this in your particular firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Always, yes. Occasionally, 'come off that. You know jolly well that you're not going to use that center-lathe, George'; although perhaps George could use a center-lathe just as well as any of us, but he was not a craftsman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you were still a child, before you started work, did your parents give you pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. Not much. My father took the view that one ought to learn money management, but we never got much money to manage. We were always kept rather short of pocket money, comp
ared with our fellows and particularly, I remember as Sunday School, the children of the working people had a lot more pocket money than we had. I can remember a very nice boy at Sunday School whose father was a cab driver and he got a shilling a week for
 
cleaning the harness of the horse when I was getting 3 or 4 pence a week. These boys probably had as many shillings in their pockets as I had pence. But we were always ... I remember we were given money at Christmas time, birthdays, and so forth, we had i
mmediately to go to the Post Office Savings Bank and deposit it. The idea of having something in the Bank was a great thing. And at that age to be given a fiver and giving it straight to a woman at the Post Office was just a dead waste of time. (laughter)

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You had a regular small amount, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about spending the money, were you expected to put it all in the Bank or could you spend some of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. I'm thinking in terms, now, of 13 to 16 years of age. I suppose at 13 we p
robably had 3d. a week, which would only get to about a shilling a week by the time we were 16. But this was nobody's business, that was for ... and one must remember that in those days the power of the pence was much more than it is now. You could get a 
quarter of a lb. of second-rate chocolate for 2d. and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it sweets and things like that that you spent your money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. And, let's face it, at 14, 15, 16 quietly buying cigarettes, as well. We hadn't to be found with them and so for
th, a great ... We used to sort of hide them in the summerhouse before we went into the home, and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Now, the next question say, did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house or family. That means apart from the domestic staff. Did you ever have occasions when relatives or friends or neighbours would step into a breach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't think it was ever necessary except, I remember when my sister Ruby had scarlet fever, she was nursed at home and we were all turned out of the h
ouse to live with Grannie. So that was rather a reverse process, wasn't it. But otherwise, for having to ask friends or relations to come and help us no, I don't think it was ever thought necessary or found necessary. I'm sure it would have been done if t
hey'd have been asked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember any occasion when your mother was it and had to be in bed, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I really can't remember when Mother was ill, until her latter days when she was living with us here. And she was a very brave woma
n, I think she'd probably felt rotten many and many a time, but she was one of these people who was the last to own up that she wasn't up to snuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You did have relatives living near, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you see these relatives fairly frequently, or not so frequently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. I had next door when we lived in Leeds an uncle and aunt, the Hampshires, whose son was about my age, Kenneth Hampshire who is ... I think I told you before, Kenneth Hampshire is the father of Susan Hampshire, the a
ctress. We used to play together and used to go into each other's houses, and our parents were very close to each other. Interestingly enough, George Hampshire - this is my father's contemporary, my uncle -was one of the nicest, finest, most wonderful men
 
I've ever known in my life, and one of the most unworldly men who always was the first to help lame dogs over stiles, and so forth and so on. A man I had the greatest possible regard for. My father used to say to him, 'George, it's all right you heading t
h
ese subscription lists and doing these sort of things, but are you making provision for your old age?' and so forth. Uncle George used to say, 'Louis, you and I both believe the same sort of things. I believe the Lord will provide, and He will provide'. I
 
don't know whether this should go on tape but it's a very amusing story. It isn't long. When Uncle George Hampshire became an old man - he'd given all his money away - and if he ever had a fiver when he went out in the morning, he came back with 4d. havin
g
 given the rest away or something of this sort. And Uncle George found himself an old man without means of looking after himself. And my father went round his many friends, went round George Hampshire's many friends in Leeds and said, 'Look, George is in 
trouble and we shall have to do something for him', and collected a lot of money, and daren't give it to Uncle George 'cos he'd have just given it away. But with this money they bought Uncle George an annuity of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12851253 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 500 a year for the rest of his life that he 
couldn't touch, but he could have this annuity. And Father went and said, 'now look, you'll be all right now'. Uncle George said, 'what did I tell you? I always said the Lord will provide and He has done, you see.' And Father used to say 'yes, the Lord an
d a few others of us!' He believed it and it came right for him. Wonderful old man. That's by the way, I'm sorry to have wasted the tape.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents have friends about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. Apart from the thing we touched on before, the fashion of thos
e days for At Homes, all women used to visit each other regularly one day a month and so forth; and my parents, I think I mentioned this before, were keen whist players and later, bridge players, and they would go out and have friends in to play cards wit
h them. They were dead against gambling, they wouldn't play for money, but they were very, very interested in playing cards and my father was interested in chess and he used to have exchange visits to play chess, and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your mother and father tend to share friends, or did they have different ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, they shared their friends, yes. I don't think they had different friends at all, in fact I don't think they would have liked that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When friends were invited into the home would they be offered anything to eat and drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
It was a teetotal home so there was no question of anything to drink, but for evenings there was usually no formal cooked meal, but the idea of dainty sort of sandwiches and coffee and this sort of thing done awf
ully well, and perhaps being unkind, in competition with the next place, to make ... do as well or better than ... that sort of thing. Informal meals of that sort, and occasionally my parents went to private dinner parties, and gave private dinner parties
. But they were not that sort of people who were terribly keen on their stomachs. I mean, they didn't worship their knives and forks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did friends tend to call in casually without an invitation, or was it always a pre-arranged ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Not always pre-arranged, but usually. Casual droppings-in ... no, I don't think there was a lot of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about neighbours, what were their relationships with neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, in Clarendon Place where we lived there was an uncle at one end, an alleged uncl
e or two, you know, the pseudo-uncles round about us who were in the same Chapel, the minister at the other end, and so forth. Yes, they visited amongst themselves. And I had ... as you know, my maternal grand parents lived in the town, both my mother's s
isters lived in the town, and my father had one old sister in Leeds, and a brother in Southport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
You've told me about chess and whist and things like that, what other things did people do when they got together with their friends? Did they have musical get-togethers as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, this was always probably both together, apart from playing whist or chess or something of that sort, the piano was always the centerpiece for singing round the piano and everybody, good, bad or indifferent, had to do thei
r best. Some was very poor stuff indeed, some was a lot better, but this was an accepted social thing as far as social contacts were concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What happened when the family moved to Harrogate, did the same sort of situation exist there, or would they
 be further removed from relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, when we went there - Harrogate is, of course, a dormitory suburb of Leeds, so that my parents had friends in Harrogate of long standing who had probably gone to Harrogate before we did, so that we didn't arri
ve as a family in Harrogate knowing nobody. And the people whom my parents did know made some effort to bring them into the Harrogate picture. And, of course, my parents joined the Methodist chapel and again got into the Methodist circle. I think it was r
e
garded as a ... these expressions sound so horrible today, but rather a social step-up in the world when we went to Harrogate. Anyway, we certainly had a better neighbourhood, socially a better neighbourhood in Harrogate than we did in Leeds, and I think 
the Harrogate atmosphere, false as it was, was a little bit above the level of the social life in Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 But the actual life that your parents and your family led would be somewhat similar, would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, except that at that time when we went to live in Harrogate we lived in a place called \{BLANK\}
 Road, opposite a very good bowling green, croquet club and tennis club, and my father learned, then, to play bowls, my mother learned to play croquet and a jolly good croquet player she became, and my el
der sisters and brother were in the tennis club, which was the other side of the road from where we lived. So summer-wise - by which time we'd given up the Bridlington cottage - summer-wise we spend across the road in this bowling croquet and tennis thing
. And we younger ones used to go and watch and help to mark out the courts and make ourselves a bit of a nuisance.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We've mentioned social class and this sort of thing avaguely as we've been going along. Trying to think of your feelings as a youngster 
and not looking back on it now, in the time prior to 1918 did you, yourself, think of some people belonging to one social class and others to a different one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I'm afraid we did, you know. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Even as a child you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, there was a bit of 'them and us'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Would you like to tell me a little bit about it. What did you conceive the different social classes to be? Would it be simpler if we spoke first about Leeds and then about Harrogate, or is the same going to apply to both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I think I would rather go on to Harrogate now because I was rather young in Leeds to form views of that sort, so let us talk about my very early 'teens in Harrogate, shall we, before 1918. Well, there was the working class, the artisan, the manual worker.
 
I don't think we differentiated in our minds between the skilled artisan and the unskilled artisan, they were working class. We were taught not to look down on them, that they were often the salt of the earth, and many of them were; but they were uncomfor
t
able in our presence and we were a bit uncomfortable in theirs and God bless them, and they God blessed us, we hoped, and that was that. The next thing was the small tradesman who was less regarded than the working man. The working man was regarded as fat
h
er a fine type of person; the small tradesman was rather regarded as the smart alec, the man who fawned on you as long as you bought your drapery and linen from him, and so forth and so on. The small tradesman was regarded rather with a bit of contempt. T
h
e commercial type, the manufacturer, that sort of type was our type - our sort of people - and we rather - my parents - were pleased to be admitted and to have as friends anybody in the professional classes, a doctor, a lawyer, an accountant, and so forth
. It was nice to have them for your friends. I'm being horrible about this, but this is ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, this is the sort of thing that I want. Do you mean that they felt that the professional classes were just that little bit above and they were gratified that they were accepted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
That's just what I was going to day, yes. And my father hadn't had the benefit of ... he'd had a grammar school education but he'd had to work from early on all his life and he was a man of some erudition, but he'd done it himsel
f and I think he felt that if he'd had a better opportunity he would have been a professional man himself, and he was pleased that professional people regarded him as worthy of his ... their steel and he could cope with them and live socially with them on
 
that level, and it pleased him. And my mother, I think, probably had a better background than my father, but she was the old type of wife, God bless them, who said 'this is what your father wants, this is what we must do', and fitted in very well with all
 these sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Had she come from a fairly well-to-do background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. Her father, my maternal grandparents was a wholesale contractor in the vegetable line. What happened, he used to go round buying acres of wheat before it was ... in fac
t, before it was sown he would provide the money to seed and say 'I will give you so much for the crop next autumn' and take a chance whether it was a good season or a bad season. And I don't know whether you know, around Leeds - then, as now - rhubarb wa
s
 a great crop. There's an old saying that there's never a good champagne year in France unless there's been a good rhybarb year in Leeds. But thousands of acres of rhubarb he would buy before it was grown, and perhaps imposed on the growers who hadn't the
 capital to capitalize it, but he made a competence from this sort of thing. And Mother, I forget when she was born, it'd down there ... but she went to a boarding school which was almost incredibly advanced in her day and generation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would that constitute all the social classes living in the area, would you say, or would there be ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we didn't ... there was no nobility, we didn't know any of the nobility and I don't think there was any to know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Now, you say you weren't brought up to 
look down on the working man, as it were. Were you brought up at all to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we were always taught to, again using these awful words - whoever hears this type will think 'what a prig that 
man was!' - it was always impressed on us that anybody whom we regarded as our social inferiors had to be treated with more courtesy than our equals. Be rude to your equals if you must, but treat your social inferiors with that added courtesy as an exampl
e to them. It sounds horried, I bet it does, but I've tried to convey a mood rather than anything that was said in so many words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Were you taught to touch your cap to anyone, and if so to what sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes. We were always taught to rai
se our caps to any lady, or to the charwoman. You know, to any member of that sex, irrespective of class. And we raised our caps to our father and his friends, to our schoolmasters, and so forth. I think there was more of that sort of thing done then than
 there is today. And I always called my father 'sir', until I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11172854 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 , I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there anybody else you would call 'sir'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Only my schoolmasters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was there anybody that you'd call 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these sort of distinctive ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, yes. Again, this was notin any way confined to my parents, but the workmen, the jobbing gardener, the man who did the little jobs, the plumber who came to repair the pipes, those 
sort of people, they would always touch their forelock to the people for whom they were working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about in the street, you know, just meeting casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't think the men, the working men, would raise their hats. They'd be courteous and g
ive Mr. Walker or Mr. Smith 'good morning', but there was no groveling or no ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who would you say were considered the most important people in your district?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Again in Harrogate, I fear that the measure of importance was often related to the me
asure ... the depth of pocket, otherwise that shockingly bad yard - stick of personal wealth, although we knew ... my parents knew some people of wealth for whom they had the greatest disregard because they were vulgar. They couldn't bear ostentation or v
ulgarity or flaunting. These sort of people they didn't care to know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
What sort of people did the various categories normally associate with? The one that's listed here first is shopkeepers. You have suggested that shopkeepers were rather ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Ye
s. The attitude to shopkeepers was some were very fine, and my parents had some retailers who were friends. But beware, take care in making friends with a shopkeeper because he'll probably expect you to spend your money at his shop and if you didn't he su
l
ked, and that spoilt friendship, so it was better not to make a friendship of that sort to have it spoiled, or to have your choice of shops restricted by the fact that you had friends who were retailers. You'd to take great care when you made a retailer y
our friend. This was the unspoken sort of attitude.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
What sort of people do you think the retailers themselves, the shopkeepers themselves, would have as their friends? Apart from trying to cultivate friendships for the sake of business? Presumably they must have had some genuine friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes. I rather think the better shopkeepers in Harrogate were the people who took an interest in municipal affairs, which my father didn't. They were aldermen and councilors and always busy municipally, and not the
 least doubt, they've got their social background interwoven in that. And also, the more prosperous shopkeepers, many of them were freemasons, My father wasn't; I am, but my father never was, but that was another sort of thing. Freemasonry consists very l
argely, or did at that time, of that sort of person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Now, you've said that the minister used to come home for lunch on Sundays, sometimes. What sort of people did the clergy associate with normally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 With their own flock, I gather, and their profe
ssional brethren, no doubt. In Methodism - and I speak quite objectively 'cos I'm not a Methodist now - there a circuit system, you know, in each town. In a big town like Leeds there'd be, perhaps, 24 chapels with 24 parsons, in Harrogate half that number
, and they used to associate one with another, and with their flock. I would think this is the broad picture.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about teachers, would they associate with other teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I don't know, I'm not quite sure about this. The headmaster of High Harro
gate College, this private school in Harrogate, was on not close personallfriendship with my father, but on visiting terms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did that arise primarlly from the fact of your being one of his pupils?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, no doubt. No. doubt. And I've no doubt that t
here was a bit of self - interest on both sides, the headmaster keeping in good terms with one of his parents, and the parents keeping in good terms with the headmaster to push his son along a little bit if necessary. I think there was a little bit of sel
f-interest there. But they had things in common, they could talk the same language, talk the same sort of way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about the professional classes in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, we knew, in my parents' circle, a few doctors, dentists, accountants, bankers, ba
nk managers, and so fort - if they are a profession. But that sort of thing. I don't know how you're probing, quite, there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would these sort of people tend to move in the same circle, or would they tend to branch out and associate with people from no
n-professional classes, either on the same social level money-wise, or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't think they were closed communities within themselves, no. they overlaid each other to a certain extent. Although my father was not a great social mixer, I mean he did
n't ... he was never interested, as I say, in municipal politics, nor was he interested in dining out and so forth, and I think some of his friends rather has an amused ... they liked him, but an amused regard for his rabid teetotalism. It's very difficul
t to entertain somebody who won't have a glass of wine, you know (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What about farmers, what sort of people did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You asked me about the farming community and I said that my wife was the daughter of a tenant farmer, a medium-sized farm\{BLANK\}
 about 3 miles away from Harrogate, and during our courtship I got to know that community quite well; a small village, the "gentry" consisted of the vicar and the squire, and the rest were very few owner farmers, mostly tenant farme
rs, mostly tenants of the squire. Very democratic. The children, who were tenants of the squire - whose parents were tenants of the squire - touched their forelocks to the squire and the girls would curtsey to the squire's wife. Those who were not tenants
 of the squire, the same type of people such as my wife's who didn't happen to be tenants of the squire, were told that they didn't have to touch their forelocks or curtsey to the squire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Who would they be told by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Their parents. Yes, yes. They w
ere told 'you don't have to do this, we're not Mr. Williams' tenants'. But the squire, I don't know whether he was typical or not, but he was an admirable man and so was the vicar: no side, no stand-offishness. There was no social contact between the squi
r
e and the villagers, I mean he didn't invite them into his home, but he and the vicar both played cricket with the village team, both played hockey with the village team, both participated with the village institute and both played billiards with the men,
 
and so forth, and they were never patronising but there was no social contact. I don't ever remember the vicar asking any of the villagers to dinner, in fact they'd have been very embarrassed if they had been. Neither did the squire invite anybody to the 
h
all. But I got to know them very well, and they were always nice to me and always nice to my wife and my wife's parents, and so forth. And the villagers themselves, well, everybody knew everybody else's business. You know, the usual village life. Very hel
p
ful to each other; they used to gossip and so forth and so on. If anybody was in trouble everybody would rally round: illness, and so forth, or if ... short of men at haytime or harvest, they'd got to go and help old George, he's short of 2 men, you know,
 
and this sort of thing. And he would reciprocate in this sort of way, and so forth. They were no better, no worse than you or I. They loved, they hated, they sinned and they were weak, and they were sorrowful and they were glad. They lived together comfor
tably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would your wife's parents be in a position to be able to afford the time to mix with the village community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, as much as anybody else. They'd, of course, to work 365 days of the year and never had holidays. Their holidays was taking a 
day off to go to the agricultural show, that sort of thing, you know. Very hard worked. But in the evenings there used to be village dances, village hops; tea parties, Church tea parties; men's institute; local village pub, and so forth, and in that respe
c
t the social life of the village revolved around those sort of things. And church-going at that time wasn't regarded as a chore or a bind, it was the sort of thing that ... it was the same as having your breakfast here, or dinner. Going to Church on Sunda
y evening was part of the social life, apart from your religious convictions, if any.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would that be true both in Harrogate and the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, I should think it's far more true in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Going back to Harrogate itself, did you know any employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 As well, of course, as your father who himself would be regarded as an employer, wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 He would be regarded as an employer. Would he and other employers ... what sort of people did they associate with
? Other than the sort of people you've already mentioned? Was it the norm for the employer to associate with the professional classes, or the exception?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, the norm, I would say. But remembering in Harrogate, there was very little industry in Harrog
ate apart from the domestic industries such as bakeries, laundries and things of this sort. The majority of the industrialists traveled on the 8.40 train every morning from Harrogate to Leeds, and there was a club saloon on this train which you used to su
b
scribe to, and so forth. So they met socially every morning, and on the 5.40 every evening coming back to Harrogate. But the majority of the industrialists ... they all knew each other, all the Leeds industrialists. In the same way there was another bunch
 that used to travel to Bradford from Harrogate, but mostly to Leeds, and that's where the industrialists earned their bread, and came home to sleep in Harrogate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would they mix socially in Harrogate as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, yes. Oh, yes, they didn't regard Harrogate as just a dormitory. No, they took part in the social life of the town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
When your father was semi - retired and was living in Harrogate and was doing a bit part-time, would he be mixing socially in Leeds at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No, no. His social life in Leeds came to an end when we went to Harrogate. Yes, this is almost like a knife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And this would apply to the rest of the family as well, your social life ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Faded, rapidly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 This business of going to Church and Chapel and s
o on: could you see any difference between the sorts of people who would go to Church, Church of England and Catholic, and the people who would go to non-conformist chapels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. It's more a feeling than a knowledge, is this, that the Anglicans we al
ways felt were a strata above the non-conformists, socially. We felt that the Anglicans were politically Conservative types, where the non-conformists were politically Liberal or radical backgrounds. The Catholics we didn't meet very much. They were a law
 unto themselves. We respected them, but we minded our own business and they seemed to mind theirs. We didn't know much about Catholics.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You wouldn't know whether they represented a general cross-section of the ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 I think probably they did, in
 Harrogate. For instance, there was no great Irish element in Harrogate which often loads a Catholic community. But even in Methodism in Harrogate there were 3 churches, Trinity, Oxford Street and a third whose name I disremember. But they were known coll
o
quially as "The World, The Flesh and The Devil". Trinity was The World, where the people with most of the world's goods seemed to go to; the one in the middle of the town, Oxford Street, was The Flesh, where the prosperous business community used to go to
;
 and the other one was known as The Devil, which was rather a mission church where the ... These were the steps in the social community, and we usually referred to these Chapels as The World, The Flesh and The Devil, not when our parents were listening, b
ut ... (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 And which of these did you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 We went to The World (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
What about the strength of people's religious convictions? Would you say that they were fairly strong, or was there some sort of veneer of insincerity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I think my parents .... thinking of my parents I think they were very sincere in their beliefs. I don't care to discuss whether their beliefs were right or wrong, but they were very sincere about it. All their lives they prayed together. Every night my 
father read a portion of the Bible to my mother, late at night, and on his deathbed he sent for us all - typical of the time, apart from my brother who died beforehand - he knew he was dying and most embarrassingly he confessed himself a great sinner befo
r
e he died. He had a feeling this was the sort of thing to get off his chest. His children, my generation, I'm afraid we were falling away from this sort of thing. We went to Chapel because we had to. I remember we didn't have to, we went there to please o
ur parents, but I don't think any of my sisters or myself had, at that time, any ... we were losing our childish convictions and hadn't got any others, at that time. Hadn't replaced them with anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you know any people in the working class well enough to be able to describe a particular family, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, I knew a few working class young men when I joined the YMCA and played billiards with them, and played football with them, YMCA-wise. But I don't ever remember going to their homes
 or them coming into my home. We were friendly, and so forth, but I'm afraid there was still the sort of ... "God bless the squire and his relations and keep us in our proper stations", this sort of attitude, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would you say that your group was one that would feel superior to the rest or would any of the other classes have this sort of...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I don't think we had a feeling of superiority, no.1. And my parents were horrified by ostentatiousness or boastfulness or this sort of thing. I don't t
hink we had a great feeling about class, we just knew where we'd been placed in this world and accepted it as that, but we didn't feel overwhelmed by people in a better social position than ourselves, nor did we feel superior when we were in the company o
f people who were not quite so well ... happily placed. No, I don't think there was any class feeling cush as one meets amongst people of extreme political views today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I think she was proud of her husband, and pleased that they had got on, to use an expression. They were always thrifty people and they were not mean, except in certain little particulars, but she always thanked God - I say this deliberately - thanked Go
d that He'd been good to them, and I think sneakingly she thought He'd every right to be. They'd played His game and He seemed to be playing theirs. But one of her expressions was, and she said it to her dying day, 'everything works together for good for 
those that trust The Lord', and whatever happened, you know, domestic crises - deaths, worries, illnesses, and so forth - she always had faith in God that there was reason for this and she was happy to, not understand it, but accept it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Was it possible for people at that time to move out of one social class into another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
I should think more difficult than it is today. I don't think you could put an iron curtain round classes because they overlap, to a certain extent. But one accepted that one is 
in a social strata in this society and one should not try to put on side or pretend to be something one was not, and one was rather resentful with people at the other end trying to do that with you. I think that is a fair comment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember anybody being described as 'a real gentleman' or 'a real lady'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, yes, a common expression, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You used it, I think, in relation to your uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, this is true. This is nothing to do with class at all, or speech, or social behaviour
, it was ... I remember my mother saying 'a gentleman is two words, not one'. A gentle man, and it doesn't matter whether he empties your dustbin or whether he's the prime minister of England, he is a gentle man or he is not a gentle man. This, then, was 
her attitude.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, yes, and in those days a policeman was ... mark you, he used to chase us as kids, and in those days if he caught us doing anything silly, playing with catapul
ts and this sort of thing, he'd box our ears and say 'get off home or I'll ...' and so forth. We were not frightened of him. If he caught us we'd say 'sorry, Mr. Jones' - we used to call them Mr. Smith or Mr. Jones. He was our copper, he was on our beat. 
A
nd one way of swift chastisement was the old cape they used to carry, it used to be rolled up into a firm roll and he'd clout you with the cape. He was all right. And you didn't tell your parents because you'd probably get another doubting when you got ho
m
e for what you'd done, so you kept quiet about this. And the policeman was our policeman, and in winter he'd come to the back door and he'd be asked in and he'd be given a bowl of soup or a cup of hot tea, and in summer he'd be given an iced lemonade or s
o
mething of this sort, take his helmet off, and quite contrary to police regulations he'd sit down for half an hour and have a smoke. And if there were any bad characters seen about, gypsies or anything of that sort we'd tell him and he'd say 'leave it wit
h
 me, I'll see to it'. He was our friend far more than the policeman is today because we are all ... you see, we are all lawbreakers today. As soon as you get a motorcar the policeman no longer is your friend. But it was very much the reverse in those days
 as I remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Would he drop into other people's houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Oh, yes. Oh, yes, yes, yes. I think he spent his time doing this sort of thing. I don't suppose he'd enter it just like that in his notebook, but this is what happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Your home at Harrogate: the first home was a rented home, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, this is true, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you see anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, he was a local man, a local builder, and it was a very nice house, too. My father very much wanted to buy it but the
 landlord didn't want to sell it. And we were very happy there but my father took a poor view of living in rented accommodation and that's why we eventually moved, because the landlord would not sell him the house, at any price. The landlord said 'no, I d
on't want to sell it I want it as an investment', and he wouldn't sell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What did you feel about him, as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, he was good. I mean, when landlord's repairs wanted doing he was told and he did them. My father paid the rent and the landlor
d did his duty and it was quite an amicable arrangement. There was never any difficulty between them, as I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Do you remember at any time feeling that your parents were having a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 No. No. I don't think I ... I th
ink, perhaps, they might have had before I was born, but by the time I came along, by the time I started remembering things their struggling days were over. They were never ... they were always ... as I indicated earlier my father was always threatened wi
t
h a heart and he ... all through his life his ... he told me 'it is my job through life for me to make quite sure that your mother will be all right when I die'. He wanted to make my mother secure and he'd established a competence by the time I was a smal
l boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
There's just one further section left and that's about your life at home after you left school. You continued to live at home although you were traveling into Leeds to the University: eventually, when you started fulltime work did that change yo
ur relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
In that I left home then, and lived in lodgings in Leeds, in Bramley where my the firm was that I went to. So I went into lodgings and left home at that period in time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 What date, about, would that be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About ... let me think ... about 1923 or 24.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Well, before you went to work, then. Suppose we talk about this in relation to when you were at University. I think that might be more appropriate. Did your relationship with your brother and sisters alter any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, except that ... as you know, I was the youngest of 5, they realized slowly, far more slowly than I would have wished, that I was growing up and that I was no longer a child; I thought that I was a lot more grown up than no doubt I 
was but they started accepting me slowly into their adult world and I was ... neither my brother nor any of my sisters went up to university, so I think they were rather pleased that I had gone up, and disappointed with me that I didn't do what they'd hop
ed for when I was there. But this is a sort of change in relationship you are asking about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did you spend your Sundays the same or differently? Did you go on going to Chapel on Sundays, and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Well, by this time I'd got a little motor car as 
well as my father's ... my father by this time had a motor car and a chauffeur, but I got a little thing that that I only paid the magnificent sum of 10 for, one of those little bangers. And that was one of the sources of trouble between my father and I, 
h
e didn't think it was a good idea to go off motoring on Sundays and I did, and I used to and it used to worry him. I had 6 days in the week to go motoring, why did I want to make Sunday hideous by motoring around, and so forth and so on. Just an aside the
r
e, this little banger I had - I was courting at this time, or it might have been a year our two later when I was courting my present wife - on occasion I'd say to my father 'look, can I have your car on Saturday, I'd like to take Peggy to Scarborough'. An
d he'd say, 'oh, yes, yes, you can have it with pleasure, and I think your mother and I will come with you', and I could've just killed him! (laughter)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When did he get his car?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 About 1924.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you had emerged from being a schoolboy, did you yourself begin to take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
No, I've never been terribly interested in politics and I have been a subscribing member - when I say a subscribing member I mean a guinea a year member - of the Conservative Party since about that t
ime, but I have never had any aspirations politically, either municipally or parliamentarily, and I've never worked for any political party, nor do I get hot and bothered because somebody is a member of a political party which isn't mine. It doesn't worry
 
me. In other words it wouldn't alter my social relations with a man who is a member of the Liberal or the Labour Party. I perhaps think, even to this day that I would probably not wish to have a friend who was a member of the Communist Party because I wou
ld squabble with him, with any extremist, as I would quarrel with a Mosley-ite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way, before you had your car, I mean? Or did you do different things? You continued with your swimming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes, thi
s was my life, competitive swimming, at this time, and I joined the University O.D.C. I had one idea, when I wasn't making a mess of medicine, was to become a professional soldier, but my father wouldn't hear of this at all because in those days ... two t
h
ings: he thought the profession of arms was not quite honourable - I disagreed with him on that thing - and also, to take a commission in the armed forces required a fairly heavy subsidy for several years. And for those two reasons my father wouldn't ... 
If he'd encouraged me I should have probably gone into the Army. But the O.D.C. interested me, swimming was my life as far as physical education and activities were concerned. And, of course, about this time - 1924, '25 - I started courting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Did your parents expect to meet your friends, when you were about 18-ish, something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 You mean bringing them home, and so forth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Oh, yes, I was never discouraged from bringing my friends home. In fact, I think my parents were glad to h
ave a look at what my friends were like, and one had one or two experiments with girlfriends and it was always a question of bringing them home as soon as possible, let Mother have a look at them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 When you went out at all did your parents expect to know where you were and what time you'd be back?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
Yes, yes, even into my 20's. They expected one to be home reasonably - I'm talking about 11 o'clock at night - and if not and one failed to telephone to say why, one was in the doghouse about it, and my
 parents would never go to bed until one got home even if it was 2 or 3 in the morning. One of my parents would wait up. And this was always a bit difficult because I'd lost my teetotal principles at this time, and going home occasionally and holding one'
s
 breath and talking through the side of one's mouth so one didn't breathe on anybody, and so forth, occasionally created difficulties, but I ... Do you know, the day of my father's death I daren't have told him that I took a drink. 'Daren't' is not the wo
rd: I wouldn't have hurt him by letting him know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1328737 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 One last question: when you eventually did start full time work did it change your attitude to life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2826842 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 Yes. Being brought up in Harrogate, and Harrogate is a very false sort of place, cynical
ly referred to as inhabited by people wearing plus-fours and having no breakfast. It was a remittance town, a retired people's town, and so forth. I didn't know much about the fact of production and the necessity for work until I got ... threw myself in t
h
e deep end, and only then did I begin to find out that the remittance man, the retired person, the drones, had to be kept by people who made something or did something with their lives. Yes, I think it certainly did change my outlook, or enlarge my horizo
n about these things very much.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-461\li461\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid1328737 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9379319\charrsid932031 
\par }}